# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: game-dev
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Collision detection is closely linked to calculating the distance between objects, as objects collide when the distance between them is less than or equal to zero.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Negative distances indicate that one object has penetrated another.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Performing collision detection requires more context than just the distance between the objects.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Accurately identifying the points of contact on both objects' surfaces is also essential for computing a physically accurate collision response.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The complexity of this task increases with the level of detail in the objects' representations: the more intricate the model, the greater the computational cost.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Collision detection frequently involves dynamic objects, adding a temporal dimension to distance calculations.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Instead of simply measuring distance between static objects, collision detection algorithms often aim to determine whether the objects' motion will bring them to a point in time when their distance is zero—an operation that adds significant computational overhead.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In collision detection involving multiple objects, a naive approach would require detecting collisions for all pairwise combinations of objects.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] As the number of objects increases, the number of required comparisons grows rapidly: for n objects, ${n(n-1)}/{2}$ intersection tests are needed with a naive approach.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This quadratic growth makes such an approach computationally expensive as n increases.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Due to the complexity mentioned above, collision detection is a computationally intensive process.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Nevertheless, it is essential for interactive applications like video games, robotics, and real-time physics engines.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] To manage these computational demands, extensive efforts have gone into optimizing collision detection algorithms.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A commonly used approach towards accelerating the required computations is to divide the process into two phases: the **broad phase** and the **narrow phase**.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The broad phase aims to answer the question of whether objects might collide, using a conservative but efficient approach to rule out pairs that clearly do not intersect, thus avoiding unnecessary calculations.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Objects that cannot be definitively separated in the broad phase are passed to the narrow phase.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Here, more precise algorithms determine whether these objects actually intersect.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If they do, the narrow phase often calculates the exact time and location of the intersection.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This phase aims at quickly finding objects or parts of objects for which it can be quickly determined that no further collision test is needed.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A useful property of such approach is that it is output sensitive.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In the context of collision detection this means that the time complexity of the collision detection is proportional to the number of objects that are close to each other.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] An early example of that is the I-COLLIDE where the number of required narrow phase collision tests was $O(n+m)$ where n is the number of objects and m is the number of objects at close proximity.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This is a significant improvement over the quadratic complexity of the naive approach.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Several approaches can be grouped under the spatial partitioning umbrella, which includes octrees (for 3D), quadtrees (for 2D), binary space partitioning (or BSP trees) and other, similar approaches.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If one splits space into a number of simple cells, and if two objects can be shown not to be in the same cell, then they need not be checked for intersection.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Dynamic scenes and deformable objects require updating the partitioning which can add overhead.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Bounding Volume Hierarchy (BVH) is a tree structure over a set of bounding volumes.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Collision is determined by doing a tree traversal starting from the root.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If the bounding volume of the root doesn't intersect with the object of interest, the traversal can be stopped.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If, however there is an intersection, the traversal proceeds and checks the branches for each there is an intersection.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Branches for which there is no intersection with the bounding volume can be culled from further intersection test.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Therefore, multiple objects can be determined to not intersect at once.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] BVH can be used with deformable objects such as cloth or soft-bodies but the volume hierarchy has to be adjusted as the shape deforms.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] For deformable objects we need to be concerned about self-collisions or self intersections.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Collision between two objects is computed by computing intersection between the bounding volumes of the root of the tree as there are collision we dive into the sub-trees that intersect.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Exact collisions between the actual objects, or its parts (often triangles of a triangle mesh) need to be computed only between intersecting leaves.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The same approach works for pair wise collision and self-collisions.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] During the broad-phase, when the objects in the world move or deform, the data-structures used to cull collisions have to be updated.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In cases where the changes between two frames or time-steps are small and the objects can be approximated well with axis-aligned bounding boxes, the sweep and prune algorithm can be a suitable approach.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The algorithm keeps track of currently intersecting boxes, and as objects move, re-sorting the intervals helps keep track of the status.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Once a pair of physical bodies has been selected for further investigation, collisions need to be checked more carefully.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] However, in many applications, individual objects (if they are not too deformable) are described by a set of smaller primitives, mainly triangles.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The obvious thing to do is to check all triangles $S_{j}$ against all triangles $T_{k}$ for collisions, but this involves $n^{2}$ comparisons, which is highly inefficient.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If possible, it is desirable to use a pruning algorithm to reduce the number of pairs of triangles that need to be checked.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The most widely used family of algorithms is known as the *hierarchical bounding volumes* method.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] As a preprocessing step, for each object (e.g., S and T ) calculates a hierarchy of bounding volumes.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Then, at each time step, when collisions need to be checked between S and T , the hierarchical bounding volumes are used to reduce the number of pairs of triangles under consideration.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] For simplicity, provide an example using bounding spheres, although it has been noted that spheres are undesirable in many cases.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If E is a set of triangles, a bounding sphere is pre-calculated. $B(E)$ .
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] There are many ways of choosing $B(E)$ , $B(E)$ is a sphere that completely contains E and is as small as possible.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Ahead of time, $B(S)$ and $B(T)$ can be computed.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Clearly, if these two spheres do not intersect (and that is very easy to test), then neither do S and T .
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This is not much better than an *n*-body pruning algorithm, however.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Apply this to S and T , and calculate (ahead of time) the bounding spheres $B(L(S)),B(R(S))$ and $B(L(T)),B(R(T))$ .
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The hope here is that these bounding spheres are much smaller than $B(S)$ and $B(T)$ .
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] And, if, for instance, $B(S)$ and $B(L(T))$ do not intersect, then there is no sense in checking any triangle in S against any triangle in $L(T)$ .
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] As a precomputation, take each physical body (represented by a set of triangles) and recursively decompose it into a binary tree, where each node N represents a set of triangles, and its two children represent $L(N)$ and $R(N)$ .
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] At each node in the tree, pre-compute the bounding sphere $B(N)$ .
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] When the time comes for testing a pair of objects for collision, their bounding sphere tree can be used to eliminate many pairs of triangles.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Many variants of the algorithms are obtained by choosing something other than a sphere for $B(T)$ .
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If one chooses axis-aligned bounding boxes, one gets AABBTrees.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Oriented bounding box trees are called OBBTrees.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Some trees are easier to update if the underlying object changes.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Some trees can accommodate higher order primitives such as splines instead of simple triangles.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In this phase, the objects under consideration are relatively close to each other.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Still, attempts to quickly determine if a full intersection is needed are employed first.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This step is sometimes referred to as mid-phase.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Once these tests passed (e.g. the pair of objects may be colliding) more precise algorithms determine whether these objects actually intersect.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Since checking whether two objects intersect can be a relatively expensive operation, one quick way to potentially avoid the computation is to check whether the bounding volumes enclosing the two objects intersect.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Bounding volumes are typically used in the early (pruning) stage of collision detection, so that only objects with overlapping volumes need be compared in detail.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If they don't overlap, there is no need to check the actual objects.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A false positive intersection in this case means that the bounding volumes intersect but the actual objects do not.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Different bounding volume types offer different trade-offs for these properties.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Axis-Align Bounding Boxes (AABB) and cuboids are popular due to their simplicity and quick intersection tests.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Bounding volumes such as Oriented Bounding Boxes (OBB), K-DOPs and Convex-hulls offer a tighter approximation of the enclosed shape at the expense of a more elaborate intersection test.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Objects for which pruning approaches could not rule out the possibility of a collision have to undergo an exact collision detection computation.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] According to the separating planes theorem, for any two disjoint convex objects, there exists a plane so that one object lies completely on one side of that plane, and the other object lies on the opposite side of that plane.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This property allows the development of efficient collision detection algorithms between convex objects.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Several algorithms are available for finding the closest points on the surface of two convex polyhedral objects - and determining collision.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Lin that used a variation on the simplex algorithm from linear programming and the Gilbert-Johnson-Keerthi distance algorithm are two such examples.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] These algorithms approach constant time when applied repeatedly to pairs of stationary or slow-moving objects, and every step is initialized from the previous collision check.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The result of all this algorithmic work is that collision detection can be done efficiently for thousands of moving objects in real time on typical personal computers and game consoles.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Where most of the objects involved are fixed, as is typical of video games, a priori methods using precomputation can be used to speed up execution.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Pruning is also desirable here, both *n*-body pruning and pairwise pruning, but the algorithms must take time and the types of motions used in the underlying physical system into consideration.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] When it comes to the exact pairwise collision detection, this is highly trajectory dependent, and one almost has to use a numerical root-finding algorithm to compute the instant of impact.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] At any point in time, the two triangles can be checked for intersection using the twenty planes previously mentioned.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If $P(u,v,w)$ is the plane going through points $u,v,w$ in $\mathbb {R} ^{3}$ then there are twenty planes $P(v_{i}(t),v_{j}(t),v_{k}(t))$ to track.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Each plane needs to be tracked against three vertices, this gives sixty values to track.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Using a root finder on these sixty functions produces the exact collision times for the two given triangles and the two given trajectory.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If the trajectories of the vertices are assumed to be linear polynomials in t then the final sixty functions are in fact cubic polynomials, and in this exceptional case, it is possible to locate the exact collision time using the formula for the roots of the cubic.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Some numerical analysts suggest that using the formula for the roots of the cubic is not as numerically stable as using a root finder for polynomials.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A triangle mesh object is commonly used in 3D body modeling.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Normally the collision function is a triangle to triangle intercept or a bounding shape associated with the mesh.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A triangle centroid is a center of mass location such that it would balance on a pencil tip.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The simulation need only add a centroid dimension to the physics parameters.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Given centroid points in both object and target it is possible to define the line segment connecting these two points.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The position vector of the centroid of a triangle is the average of the position vectors of its vertices.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Here the length/distance of the segment is an adjustable "hit" criteria size of segment.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] As the objects approach the length decreases to the threshold value.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A triangle sphere becomes the effective geometry test.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A sphere centered at the centroid can be sized to encompass all the triangle's vertices.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Physical simulators differ in the way they react on a collision.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Some use the softness of the material to calculate a force, which will resolve the collision in the following time steps like it is in reality.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This is very CPU intensive for low softness materials.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Some simulators estimate the time of collision by linear interpolation, roll back the simulation, and calculate the collision by the more abstract methods of conservation laws.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Some iterate the linear interpolation (Newton's method) to calculate the time of collision with a much higher precision than the rest of the simulation.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Collision detection utilizes time coherence to allow even finer time steps without much increasing CPU demand, such as in air traffic control.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] After an inelastic collision, special states of sliding and resting can occur and, for example, the Open Dynamics Engine uses constraints to simulate them.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Constraints avoid inertia and thus instability.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Implementation of rest by means of a scene graph avoids drift.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In other words, physical simulators usually function one of two ways: where the collision is detected *a posteriori* (after the collision occurs) or *a priori* (before the collision occurs).
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In addition to the *a posteriori* and *a priori* distinction, almost all modern collision detection algorithms are broken into a hierarchy of algorithms.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Often the terms "discrete" and "continuous" are used rather than *a posteriori* and *a priori*.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In the *a posteriori* case, the physical simulation is advanced by a small step, then checked to see if any objects are intersecting or visibly considered intersecting.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] At each simulation step, a list of all intersecting bodies is created, and the positions and trajectories of these objects are "fixed" to account for the collision.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This method is called *a posteriori* because it typically misses the actual instant of collision, and only catches the collision after it has actually happened.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In the *a priori* methods, there is a collision detection algorithm which will be able to predict very precisely the trajectories of the physical bodies.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The instants of collision are calculated with high precision, and the physical bodies never actually interpenetrate.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] This is called *a priori* because the collision detection algorithm calculates the instants of collision before it updates the configuration of the physical bodies.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The main benefits of the *a posteriori* methods are as follows.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In this case, the collision detection algorithm need not be aware of the myriad of physical variables; a simple list of physical bodies is fed to the algorithm, and the program returns a list of intersecting bodies.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The collision detection algorithm doesn't need to understand friction, elastic collisions, or worse, nonelastic collisions and deformable bodies.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In addition, the *a posteriori* algorithms are in effect one dimension simpler than the *a priori* algorithms.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] An *a priori* algorithm must deal with the time variable, which is absent from the *a posteriori* problem.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] On the other hand, *a posteriori* algorithms cause problems in the "fixing" step, where intersections (which aren't physically correct) need to be corrected.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Moreover, if the discrete step is too large, the collision could go undetected, resulting in an object which passes through another if it is sufficiently fast or small.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The benefits of the *a priori* algorithms are increased fidelity and stability.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] It is difficult (but not completely impossible) to separate the physical simulation from the collision detection algorithm.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] However, in all but the simplest cases, the problem of determining ahead of time when two bodies will collide (given some initial data) has no closed form solution—a numerical root finder is usually involved.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Some objects are in *resting contact*, that is, in collision, but neither bouncing off, nor interpenetrating, such as a vase resting on a table.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In all cases, resting contact requires special treatment: If two objects collide (*a posteriori*) or slide (*a priori*) and their relative motion is below a threshold, friction becomes stiction and both objects are arranged in the same branch of the scene graph.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Video games have to split their very limited computing time between several tasks.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Despite this resource limit, and the use of relatively primitive collision detection algorithms, programmers have been able to create believable, if inexact, systems for use in games.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] For a long time, video games had a very limited number of objects to treat, and so checking all pairs was not a problem.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In two-dimensional games, in some cases, the hardware was able to efficiently detect and report overlapping pixels between sprites on the screen.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In other cases, simply tiling the screen and binding each *sprite* into the tiles it overlaps provides sufficient pruning, and for pairwise checks, bounding rectangles or circles called hitboxes are used and deemed sufficiently accurate.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Three-dimensional games have used spatial partitioning methods for n -body pruning, and for a long time used one or a few spheres per actual 3D object for pairwise checks.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Exact checks are very rare, except in games attempting to simulate reality closely.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Even then, exact checks are not necessarily used in all cases.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Because games do not need to mimic actual physics, stability is not as much of an issue.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Almost all games use *a posteriori* collision detection, and collisions are often resolved using very simple rules.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] For instance, if a character becomes embedded in a wall, they might be simply moved back to their last known good location.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Some games will calculate the distance the character can move before getting embedded into a wall, and only allow them to move that far.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In many cases for video games, approximating the characters by a point is sufficient for the purpose of collision detection with the environment.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In this case, binary space partitioning trees provide a viable, efficient and simple algorithm for checking if a point is embedded in the scenery or not.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Such a data structure can also be used to handle "resting position" situation gracefully when a character is running along the ground.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Collisions between characters, and collisions with projectiles and hazards, are treated separately.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A robust simulator is one that will react to any input in a reasonable way.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] For instance, imagining a high speed racecar video game, it is conceivable that the cars would advance a substantial distance along the race track from one simulation step to the next.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] If there is a shallow obstacle on the track (such as a brick wall), it is not entirely unlikely that the car will completely leap over it, and this is very undesirable.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] These are the hallmarks of a failing collision detection and physical simulation system.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] *Big Rigs: Over the Road Racing* is an infamous example of a game with a failing or possibly missing collision detection system.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A **hitbox** is an invisible shape commonly used in video games for real-time collision detection; it is a type of bounding box.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] It is often a rectangle (in 2D games) or cuboid (in 3D) that is attached to and follows a point on a visible object (such as a model or a sprite).
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Circular or spheroidial shapes are also common, though they are still most often called "boxes".
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] It is common for animated objects to have hitboxes attached to each moving part to ensure accuracy during motion.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Hitboxes are used to detect "one-way" collisions such as a character being hit by a punch or a bullet.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] They are unsuitable for the detection of collisions with feedback (e.g. bumping into a wall) due to the difficulty experienced by both humans and AI in managing a hitbox's ever-changing locations; these sorts of collisions are typically handled with much simpler axis-aligned bounding boxes instead.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] Players may use the term "hitbox" to refer to these types of interactions regardless.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] A **hurtbox** is a hitbox used to detect incoming sources of damage.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] In this context, the term *hitbox* is typically reserved for those which deal damage.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] For example, an attack may only land if the hitbox around an attacker's punch connects with one of the opponent's hurtboxes on their body, while opposing hitboxes colliding may result in the players trading or cancelling blows, and opposing hurtboxes do not interact with each other.
[src:game-dev/collision-detection] The term is not standardized across the industry; some games reverse their definitions of *hitbox* and *hurtbox*, while others only use "hitbox" for both sides.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] ECS prioritizes composition over inheritance.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Every entity is defined not by a type hierarchy, but by the components associated with it.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Systems act globally over all entities that have the required components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] For example, a food system might iterate through every entity with a relevant component tracking hunger, and act on them to push them a little away from satiation at time intervals.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Entities lacking the component like terrain or items would be naturally ignored by the food system.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Due to an ambiguity in the English language, an interpretation of the name is that an ECS is a system comprising entities and components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In the 2002 talk at GDC, Scott Bilas compared a C++ object system and his new custom component system.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] This is consistent with a traditional use of *system* terms in general systems engineering with Common Lisp Object System and type system as examples.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Although mostly found in video game development, the ECS can be useful in other domains, such as in robotics simulators like Gazebo.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] ECS combines orthogonal, well-established ideas in general computer science and programming language theory.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] For example, components can be seen as a mixin idiom in various programming languages.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Components are a specialized case under the general delegation approach and meta-object protocol.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] That is, any complete component object system can be expressed with the *templates* and *empathy* model within The Orlando Treaty vision of object-oriented programming.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] An entity represents a general-purpose object.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In a game engine context, for example, every coarse game object is represented as an entity.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Usually, it only consists of a unique ID.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] as possessing a particular aspect, and (the component) holds the data needed to model that aspect.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] For example, every game object that can take damage might have a Health component associated with its entity.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] A system is a process that acts on all entities with the desired components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] For example, a physics system may query for entities having mass, velocity and position components, iterate over the results, and do physics calculations for each entity using the set of components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The behavior of an entity can be changed at runtime by systems that add, remove or modify components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] This eliminates the ambiguity problems of deep and wide inheritance hierarchies often found in object-oriented programming techniques that are difficult to understand, maintain, and extend.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Common ECS approaches are highly compatible with, and are often combined with, data-oriented design techniques.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Data for all instances of a component are contiguously stored together in physical memory, enabling efficient memory access for systems that operate over many entities.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In 1963, Ivan Sutherland's Sketchpad stored the visual elements of a drawing using an early form of an ECS.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Instead of encapsulating points in different objects (e.g. lines, circles, rectangles) points were stored in a ring buffer, and visual elements were only referencing them.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] When moving a point, this allowed updating all the shapes and constraints using it.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In 1998, *Thief: The Dark Project* pioneered an ECS.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The engine was later used for its sequel, as well as *System Shock 2*.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In 2002, Scott Bilas of Gas Powered Games (Dungeon Siege) gave a seminal talk on ECS.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] This inspired numerous later well-known implementations.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In early January 2007, Mick West who worked on the Tony Hawk series, shared his experiences on the process of ECS adoption at Neversoft.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Also in 2007, the team working on *Operation Flashpoint: Dragon Rising* experimented with ECS designs, including those inspired by Bilas/*Dungeon Siege*, and Adam Martin later wrote a detailed account of ECS design, including definitions of core terminology and concepts.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In particular, Martin's work popularized the ideas of systems as a first-class element, entities as identifiers, components as raw data, and code stored in systems, not in components or entities.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In 2015, Apple Inc. introduced GameplayKit, an API framework for iOS, macOS and tvOS game development that includes an implementation of ECS.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In October 2018 the company Unity released its megacity demo that utilized a tech stack built on an ECS.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Unity's ECS runs on a powerful optimized architecture known as DOTS, which "empowers creators to scale processing in a highly performant manner".
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The data layout of different ECS's can differ as well as the definition of components, how they relate to entities, and how systems access entities' components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Adam Martin defines in his blog series what he considers an Entity–Component–System.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] An entity only consists of an ID for accessing components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] It is a common practice to use a unique ID for each entity.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Some of these advantages can also be achieved using smart pointers.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Components have no game code (behavior) inside of them.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The components don't have to be located physically together with the entity, but should be easy to find and access using the entity.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Unity's layout has tables, each with columns of components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] In this system an entity *type* is based on the components it holds.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] For every entity *type* there is a table (called an *archetype*) holding columns of components that match the components used in the entity.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] To access a particular entity one must find the correct archetype (table) and index into each column to get each corresponding component for that entity.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The normal way to transmit data between systems is to store the data in components, and then have each system access the component sequentially.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] For example, the position of an object can be updated regularly.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] This position is then used by other systems.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] If there are a lot of different infrequent events, a lot of flags will be needed in one or more components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Systems will then have to monitor these flags every iteration, which can become inefficient.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] A solution could be to use the observer pattern.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] All systems that depend on an event subscribe to it.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The action from the event will thus only be executed once, when it happens, and no polling is needed.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The ECS has no trouble with dependency problems commonly found in object-oriented programming since components are simple data buckets and have no dependencies.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Each system will typically query the set of components an entity must have for the system to operate on it.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] For example, a render system might register the model, transformations, and drawable components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] When it runs, the system will perform its logic on any entity that has all of those components.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Other entities are simply skipped, with no need for complex dependency trees.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] However, this can be a place for bugs to hide, since propagating values from one system to another through components may be hard to debug.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] ECS may be used where uncoupled data needs to be bound to a given lifetime.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The ECS uses composition, rather than inheritance trees.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] An entity will be typically made up of an ID and a list of components that are attached to it.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] Any game object can be created by adding the correct components to an entity.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] This allows the developer to easily add features to an entity, without any dependency issues.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] For example, a player entity could have a *bullet* component added to it, which would then meet the requirements to be manipulated by some *bulletHandler* system, which then could result in that bullet doing damage to other objects by running into them.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] The merits of using ECS for storing the game state have been proclaimed by many game developers like Adam Martin.
[src:game-dev/entity-component-system] One good example is the blog posts by Richard Lord, where he discusses the merits and why ECS-designed game data storage systems are so useful.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] The temporal sensitivity and resolution of human vision vary depending on the type and characteristics of the visual stimulus, and it differs between individuals.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] The human visual system can process 10 to 12 images per second and perceive them individually, while higher rates are perceived as motion.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Modulated light (such as a computer display) is perceived as stable by the majority of participants in studies when the rate is higher than 50 FPS.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] This perception of modulated light as steady is known as the flicker fusion threshold.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] However, when the modulated light is non-uniform and contains an image, the flicker fusion threshold can be much higher, in the hundreds of hertz.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] With regard to image recognition, people have been found to recognize a specific image in an unbroken series of different images, each of which lasts as little as 13 milliseconds.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Persistence of vision sometimes accounts for very short single-millisecond visual stimulus having a perceived duration of between 100 ms and 400 ms.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Multiple stimuli that are very short are sometimes perceived as a single stimulus, such as a 10 ms green flash of light immediately followed by a 10 ms red flash of light perceived as a single yellow flash of light.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Early silent films had stated frame rates anywhere from 16 to 24 frames per second (FPS), but since the cameras were hand-cranked, the rate often changed during the scene to fit the mood.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Projectionists could also change the frame rate in the theater by adjusting a rheostat controlling the voltage powering the film-carrying mechanism in the projector.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Film companies often intended for theaters to show their silent films at a higher frame rate than that at which they were filmed.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] These frame rates were enough for the sense of motion, but it was perceived as jerky motion.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] To minimize the perceived flicker, projectors employed dual- and triple-blade shutters, so each frame was displayed two or three times, increasing the flicker rate to 48 or 72 FPS and reducing eye strain.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Thomas Edison said that 46 frames per second was the minimum needed for the eye to perceive motion: "Anything less will strain the eye." In the mid to late 1920s, the frame rate for silent film increased to 20–26 FPS.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] When sound film was introduced in 1926, variations in film speed were no longer tolerated, as the human ear is more sensitive than the eye to changes in frequency.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Many theaters had shown silent films at 22 to 26 FPS, which is why the industry chose 24 FPS for sound film as a compromise.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] From 1927 to 1930, as various studios updated equipment, the rate of 24 FPS became standard for 35 mm sound film.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] At 24 FPS, the film travels through the projector at a rate of 456 millimetres (18.0 in) per second.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] This allowed simple two-blade shutters to give a projected series of images at 48 per second, satisfying Edison's recommendation.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Many modern 35 mm film projectors use three-blade shutters to give 72 images per second—each frame is flashed on screen three times.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] In drawn animation, moving characters are often animated *on twos*, meaning one drawing is displayed for every two frames of film.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Since film typically runs at 24 frames per second, this results in a display of only 12 drawings per second.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Even though the image update rate is low, the fluidity is satisfactory for most subjects.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] However, when a character is required to perform a quick movement, it is usually necessary to revert to animating *on ones*, as *twos* are too slow to convey the motion adequately.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] A blend of the two techniques keeps the eye fooled and controls production cost.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Animation for most Saturday morning cartoons, first introduced in the mid-1960s, was produced as cheaply as possible and was most often shot on *threes* or even *fours*, i.e., three or four frames per drawing.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] This translates to only 8 or 6 drawings per second, respectively.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Anime is also usually drawn on threes or twos.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Due to the mains frequency of electric grids, analog television broadcast was developed with frame rates of 50 FPS (most of the world) or 60 FPS (Canada, US, Mexico, Philippines, Japan, South Korea).
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] The frequency of the electricity grid was extremely stable and therefore it was logical to use for synchronization.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] The introduction of color television technology made it necessary to lower that 60 FPS frequency by 0.1% to avoid "dot crawl", a display artifact appearing on legacy black-and-white displays, showing up on highly color-saturated surfaces.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] It was found that by lowering the frame rate by 0.1%, the undesirable effect was minimized.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] As of 2025, video transmission standards in North America, Japan, and South Korea are still based on 60/1.001 ≈ 59.94 images per second.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Confusingly, *interlaced* formats are customarily stated at half their image rate, 29.97/25 FPS, and *double* their image height, but these statements are purely custom; in each format, 60 images per second are produced.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] A resolution of 1080i produces 59.94 or 50 1920 × 540 images, each squashed to half-height in the photographic process and stretched back to fill the screen on playback in a television set.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] The 720p format produces 59.94/50 or 29.97/25 1280 × 720 images, not squeezed, so that no expansion or squeezing of the image is necessary.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] This confusion was industry-wide in the early days of digital video software, with much software being written incorrectly, the developers believing that only 29.97 images were expected each second.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] While it was true that each picture element was polled and sent only 29.97 times per second, the pixel location immediately below that one was polled 1/60 of a second later, part of a completely separate image for the next 1/60-second frame.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] At its native 24 FPS rate, film could not be displayed on 60 FPS video without the necessary pulldown process, often leading to *judder*: to convert 24 frames per second into 60 frames per second, every odd frame is repeated, playing twice, while every even frame is tripled.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] This creates uneven motion, appearing stroboscopic.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Other conversions have similar uneven frame doubling.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Newer video standards support 120, 240, or 300 frames per second, so frames can be evenly sampled for standard frame rates such as 24, 48 and 60 FPS film or 25, 30, 50 or 60 FPS video.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Of course these higher frame rates may also be displayed at their native rates.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] In computer video games, frame rate plays an important part in the experience as, unlike film, games are rendered in real-time.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] 60 frames per second has for a long time been considered the minimum frame rate for smoothly animated game play.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Video games designed for PAL markets, before the sixth generation of video game consoles, had lower frame rates by design due to the 50 Hz output.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] This noticeably made fast-paced games, such as racing or fighting games, run slower; less frequently developers accounted for the frame rate difference and altered the game code to achieve (nearly) identical pacing across both regions, with varying degrees of success.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Computer monitors marketed to competitive PC gamers can hit 360, 500 FPS, or more.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] High frame rates make action scenes look less blurry, such as sprinting through the wilderness in an open world game, spinning rapidly to face an opponent in a first-person shooter, or keeping track of details during an intense fight in a multiplayer online battle arena.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Some people may have difficulty perceiving the differences between high frame rates, though.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Frame time is related to frame rate, but it measures the time between frames.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] A game could maintain an average of 60 frames per second but appear choppy because of a poor frame time.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Game reviews sometimes average the worst 1% of frame rates, reported as the 99th percentile, to measure how choppy the game appears.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] A small difference between the average frame rate and 99th percentile would generally indicate a smooth experience.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] To mitigate the choppiness of poorly optimized games, players can set frame rate caps closer to their 99% percentile.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] When a game's frame rate is different from the display's refresh rate, screen tearing can occur.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Vsync mitigates this, but it caps the frame rate to the display's refresh rate, increases input lag, and introduces judder.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Variable refresh rate displays automatically set their refresh rate equal to the game's frame rate, as long as it is within the display's supported range.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Frame rate up-conversion (FRC) is the process of increasing the temporal resolution of a video sequence by synthesizing one or more intermediate frames between two consecutive frames.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] A low frame rate causes aliasing, yields abrupt motion artifacts, and degrades the video quality.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Consequently, the temporal resolution is an important factor affecting video quality.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Algorithms for FRC are widely used in applications, including visual quality enhancement, video compression and slow-motion video generation.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Most FRC methods can be categorized into optical flow or kernel-based and pixel hallucination-based methods.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Flow-based methods linearly combine predicted optical flows between two input frames to approximate flows from the target intermediate frame to the input frames.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] They also propose flow reversal (projection) for more accurate image warping.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Moreover, there are algorithms that give different weights of overlapped flow vectors depending on the object depth of the scene via a flow projection layer.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] Pixel hallucination-based methods use deformable convolution to the center frame generator by replacing optical flows with offset vectors.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] There are algorithms that also interpolate middle frames with the help of deformable convolution in the feature domain.
[src:game-dev/frame-rate] However, since these methods directly hallucinate pixels, unlike the flow-based FRC methods, the predicted frames tend to be blurry when fast-moving objects are present.
[src:game-dev/game-design] In academic research, game design falls within the field of game studies (not to be confused with game theory, which studies strategic decision making, primarily in non-game situations).
[src:game-dev/game-design] Game design is part of a game's development from concept to final form.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Typically, the development process is iterative, with repeated phases of testing and revision.
[src:game-dev/game-design] During revision, additional design or re-design may be needed.
[src:game-dev/game-design] A game designer (or inventor) is a person who invents a game's concept, central mechanisms, rules, and themes.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Game designers may work alone or in teams.
[src:game-dev/game-design] A game developer is a person who fleshes out the details of a game's design, oversees its testing, and revises the game in response to player feedback.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Often game designers also do development work on the same project.
[src:game-dev/game-design] However, some publishers commission extensive development of games to suit their target audience after licensing a game from a designer.
[src:game-dev/game-design] For larger games, such as collectible card games, designers and developers work in teams with separate roles.
[src:game-dev/game-design] A game artist creates visual art for games.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Game artists are often vital to role-playing games and collectible card games.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Many graphic elements of games are created by the designer when producing a prototype of the game, revised by the developer based on testing, and then further refined by the artist and combined with artwork as a game is prepared for publication or release.
[src:game-dev/game-design] A game concept is an idea for a game, briefly describing its core play mechanisms, objectives, themes, and who the players represent.
[src:game-dev/game-design] A game concept may be pitched to a game publisher in a similar manner as film ideas are pitched to potential film producers.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Alternatively, game publishers holding a game license to intellectual property in other media may solicit game concepts from several designers before picking one to design a game.
[src:game-dev/game-design] During design, a game concept is fleshed out.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Mechanisms are specified in terms of components (boards, cards, tokens, etc.) and rules.
[src:game-dev/game-design] The play sequence and possible player actions are defined, as well as how the game starts, ends, and win conditions (if any).
[src:game-dev/game-design] A game prototype is a draft version of a game used for testing.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Uses of prototyping include exploring new game design possibilities and technologies.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Play testing is a major part of game development.
[src:game-dev/game-design] During testing, players play the prototype and provide feedback on its gameplay, the usability of its components, the clarity of its goals and rules, ease of learning, and entertainment value.
[src:game-dev/game-design] During testing, various balance issues may be identified, requiring changes to the game's design.
[src:game-dev/game-design] The developer then revises the design, components, presentation, and rules before testing it again.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Later testing may take place with focus groups to test consumer reactions before publication.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Many games have ancient origins and were not designed in the modern sense, but gradually evolved over time through play.
[src:game-dev/game-design] The rules of these games were not codified until early modern times and their features gradually developed and changed through the folk process.
[src:game-dev/game-design] For example, sports (see history of sports), gambling, and board games are known, respectively, to have existed for at least nine thousand, six thousand, and four thousand years.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Tabletop games played today whose descent can be traced from ancient times include chess, go, pachisi, mancala, and pick-up sticks.
[src:game-dev/game-design] These games are not considered to have had a designer or been the result of a contemporary design process.
[src:game-dev/game-design] After the rise of commercial game publishing in the late 19th century, many games that had formerly evolved via folk processes became commercial properties, often with custom scoring pads or preprepared material.
[src:game-dev/game-design] For example, the similar public domain games Generala, Yacht, and Yatzy led to the commercial game Yahtzee in the mid-1950s.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Today, many commercial games, such as Taboo, Balderdash, Pictionary, or Time's Up!, are descended from traditional parlour games.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Adapting traditional games to become commercial properties is an example of game design.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Similarly, many sports, such as soccer and baseball, are the result of folk processes, while others were designed, such as basketball, invented in 1891 by James Naismith.
[src:game-dev/game-design] The first games in a new medium are frequently adaptations of older games.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Later games often exploit the distinctive properties of a new medium.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Adapting older games and creating original games for new media are both examples of game design.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Technological advances have provided new media for games throughout history.
[src:game-dev/game-design] For example, accurate topographic maps produced as lithographs and provided free to Prussian officers helped popularize wargaming.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Cheap bookbinding (printed labels wrapped around cardboard) led to mass-produced board games with custom boards.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Inexpensive (hollow) lead figurine casting contributed to the development of miniature wargaming.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Games can be designed for entertainment, education, exercise or experimental purposes.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Additionally, elements and principles of game design can be applied to other interactions, in the form of gamification.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Games have historically inspired seminal research in the fields of probability, artificial intelligence, economics, and optimization theory.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Applying game design to itself is a current research topic in metadesign.
[src:game-dev/game-design] By learning through play children can develop social and cognitive skills, mature emotionally, and gain the self-confidence required to engage in new experiences and environments.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Key ways that young children learn include playing, being with other people, being active, exploring and new experiences, talking to themselves, communicating with others, meeting physical and mental challenges, being shown how to do new things, practicing and repeating skills, and having fun.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Play develops children's content knowledge and provides children the opportunity to develop social skills, competencies, and disposition to learn.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Play-based learning is based on a Vygotskian model of scaffolding where the teacher pays attention to specific elements of the play activity and provides encouragement and feedback on children's learning.
[src:game-dev/game-design] When children engage in real-life and imaginary activities, play can be challenging in children's thinking.
[src:game-dev/game-design] To extend the learning process, sensitive intervention can be provided with adult support when necessary during play-based learning.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Different types of games pose specific game design issues.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Board game design is the development of rules and presentational aspects of a board game.
[src:game-dev/game-design] When a player takes part in a game, it is the player's self-subjection to the rules that create a sense of purpose for the duration of the game.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Maintaining the players' interest throughout the gameplay experience is the goal of board game design.
[src:game-dev/game-design] To achieve this, board game designers emphasize different aspects such as social interaction, strategy, and competition, and target players of differing needs by providing for short versus long-play, and luck versus skill.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Beyond this, board game design reflects the culture in which the board game is produced.
[src:game-dev/game-design] The most ancient board games known today are over 5000 years old.
[src:game-dev/game-design] They are frequently abstract in character and their design is primarily focused on a core set of simple rules.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Of those that are still played today, games like go (c.
[src:game-dev/game-design] 600 AD) have gone through many presentational and/or rule variations.
[src:game-dev/game-design] In the case of chess, for example, new variants are developed constantly, to focus on certain aspects of the game, or just for variation's sake.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Traditional board games date from the nineteenth and early twentieth century.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Whereas ancient board game design was primarily focused on rules alone, traditional board games were often influenced by Victorian mores.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Academic (e.g. history and geography) and moral didacticism were important design features for traditional games, and Puritan associations between dice and the Devil meant that early American game designers eschewed their use in board games entirely.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Even traditional games that did use dice, like *Monopoly* (based on the 1906 *The Landlord's Game*), were rooted in educational efforts to explain political concepts to the masses.
[src:game-dev/game-design] By the 1930s and 1940s, board game design began to emphasize amusement over education, and characters from comic strips, radio programmes, and (in the 1950s) television shows began to be featured in board game adaptations.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Recent developments in modern board game design can be traced to the 1980s in Germany, and have led to the increased popularity of "German-style board games" (also known as "Eurogames" or "designer games").
[src:game-dev/game-design] The design emphasis of these board games is to give players meaningful choices.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Moon has described as "elegant game design".
[src:game-dev/game-design] The concept of elegant game design has been identified by *The Boston Globe'*s Leon Neyfakh as related to Mihaly Csikszentmihalyi's the concept of "flow" from his 1990 book, "Flow: The Psychology of Optimal Experience".
[src:game-dev/game-design] Modern technological advances have had a democratizing effect on board game production, with services like Kickstarter providing designers with essential startup capital and tools like 3D printers facilitating the production of game pieces and board game prototypes.
[src:game-dev/game-design] A modern adaptation of figure games are miniature wargames like *Warhammer 40,000*.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Card games can be designed as gambling games, such as Poker, or simply for fun, such as Go Fish.
[src:game-dev/game-design] As cards are typically shuffled and revealed gradually during play, most card games involve randomness, either initially or during play, and hidden information, such as the cards in a player's hand.
[src:game-dev/game-design] How players play their cards, revealing information and interacting with previous plays as they do so, is central to card game design.
[src:game-dev/game-design] In partnership card games, such as Bridge, rules limiting communication between players on the same team become an important part of the game design.
[src:game-dev/game-design] This idea of limited communication has been extended to cooperative card games, such as Hanabi.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Dice games differ from card games in that each throw of the dice is an independent event, whereas the odds of a given card being drawn are affected by all the previous cards drawn or revealed from a deck.
[src:game-dev/game-design] For this reason, dice game design often centers around forming scoring combinations and managing re-rolls, either by limiting their number, as in Yahtzee or by introducing a press-your-luck element, as in *Can't Stop*.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Casino game design can entail the creation of an entirely new casino game, the creation of a variation on an existing casino game, or the creation of a new side bet on an existing casino game.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Casino game mathematician, Michael Shackleford has noted that it is much more common for casino game designers today to make successful variations than entirely new casino games.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Gambling columnist John Grochowski points to the emergence of community-style slot machines in the mid-1990s, for example, as a successful variation on an existing casino game type.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Unlike the majority of other games which are designed primarily in the interest of the player, one of the central aims of casino game design is to optimize the house advantage and maximize revenue from gamblers.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Successful casino game design works to provide entertainment for the player and revenue for the gambling house.
[src:game-dev/game-design] To maximise player entertainment, casino games are designed with simple easy-to-learn rules that emphasize winning (i.e. whose rules enumerate many victory conditions and few loss conditions), and that provide players with a variety of different gameplay postures (e.g. card hands).
[src:game-dev/game-design] Player entertainment value is also enhanced by providing gamblers with familiar gaming elements (e.g. dice and cards) in new casino games.
[src:game-dev/game-design] To maximise success for the gambling house, casino games are designed to be easy for croupiers to operate and for pit managers to oversee.
[src:game-dev/game-design] The two most fundamental rules of casino game design are that the games must be non-fraudable (including being as nearly as possible immune from advantage gambling) and that they must mathematically favor the house winning.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Shackleford suggests that the optimum casino game design should give the house an edge of smaller than 5%.
[src:game-dev/game-design] The design of tabletop role-playing games typically requires the establishment of setting, characters, and gameplay rules or mechanics.
[src:game-dev/game-design] After a role-playing game is produced, additional design elements are often devised by the players themselves.
[src:game-dev/game-design] In many instances, for example, character creation is left to the players.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Early role-playing game theories developed on indie role-playing game design forums in the early 2000s.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Game design is a topic of study in the academic field of game studies.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Game studies is a discipline that deals with the critical study of games, game design, players, and their role in society and culture.
[src:game-dev/game-design] Prior to the late-twentieth century, the academic study of games was rare and limited to fields such as history and anthropology.
[src:game-dev/game-design] As the video game revolution took off in the early 1980s, so did academic interest in games, resulting in a field that draws on diverse methodologies and schools of thought.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] A **game engine** is a software framework primarily designed for video game development, which may include specialized software libraries and packages, such as level editors.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] The term "engine" is a direct analogue of "software engine", having it employed across sectors of the software industry.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Furthermore, *game engine* may also refer to the integrated development environment as an interface behind the given framework, typically a suite of visual development tools and features for developing video games.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Game developers can use game engines to create and publish video games across platforms, such as desktops, mobile devices, video game consoles, and other types of computers.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] The core functionalities commonly covered by a game engine are a 2D or 3D renderer, physics engine, audio engine, scripting, animation, artificial intelligence, networking, streaming, memory management, threads, localization support, scene graph, and cinematics.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Game engine developers often economize game development through reuse or adaptation of abstractions built into game engines for production of various games, or through porting of videogames from a single to other target platforms.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] In many cases, game engines provide a suite of visual development tools in addition to reusable software components.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] These tools are generally provided in an integrated development environment to enable simplified, rapid development of games in a data-driven manner.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Game-engine developers often attempt to preempt implementer needs by developing robust software suites, which include many elements a game developer may need to build a game.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Most game-engine suites provide facilities that ease development, such as graphics, sound, physics and artificial intelligence (AI) functions.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Like other types of middleware, game engines usually provide platform abstraction, allowing the same game to run on various platforms (including game consoles and personal computers) with few, if any, changes made to the game source code.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Often, programmers design game engines with a component-based architecture that allows specific systems in the engine to be replaced or extended with more specialized (and often more expensive) game-middleware components.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Some game engines comprise a series of loosely-connected game middleware components that can be selectively combined to create a custom engine, instead of the more common approach of extending or customizing a flexible integrated product.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] However achieved, extensibility remains a high priority for game engines due to the wide variety of uses for which they are applied.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Despite the specificity of the name "game engine", end users often re-purpose game engines for other kinds of interactive applications with real-time graphical requirements—such as marketing demos, architectural visualizations, training simulations, and modeling environments.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Some game engines only provide real-time 3D rendering capabilities instead of the wide range of functionality needed by games.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] These engines rely upon the game developer to implement the rest of this functionality or to assemble it from other game-middleware components.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] These types of engines are generally referred to as a "graphics engine", "rendering engine", or "3D engine" instead of the all-encompassing term "game engine".
[src:game-dev/game-engine] This terminology is inconsistently used, as many full-featured 3D game engines are simply referred to as "3D engines".
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Examples of graphics engines include: Crystal Space, Genesis3D, Irrlicht, OGRE, RealmForge, Truevision3D, and Vision Engine.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Modern game- or graphics-engines generally provide a scene graph—an object-oriented representation of the 3D game-world which often simplifies game design and can be used for more efficient rendering of vast virtual worlds.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Most game engines or graphics engines use a Graphics API, which eases communication with the GPU.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] But older games did not have hardware acceleration or GPUs and had to build their own software renderer.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] As technology ages, the components of an engine may become obsolete or insufficient for the requirements of a given project.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Since the complexity of programming an entirely new engine may result in unwanted delays (or necessitate that a project restart from the beginning), an engine-development team may elect to update their existing engine with newer functionality or components.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Game engines are not limited to use in the video game field, and have found uses in other scientific fields.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Part of this is due to game engines being optimized for consumer-grade computing equipment rather than high-performance computing, allowing researchers to develop programs for their use on lower cost machines.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Game engines also simplify many of the computing operations needed for scientific software, including graphics, networking, and interactivity, reducing the need to develop these features themselves.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Before game engines, games were typically written as singular entities: a game for the Atari 2600, for example, had to be designed from the bottom up to make optimal use of the display hardware—this core display routine is now called the kernel by developers of games for older systems.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Other platforms had more leeway, but even when display was not a concern, memory constraints usually sabotaged attempts to create the data-heavy design that an engine needs.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Even on more accommodating platforms, very little could be reused between games.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] The rapid advance of arcade hardware—which was the leading edge of the market at the time—meant that most of the code would have to be thrown out afterwards anyway, as later generations of games would use completely different game designs that took advantage of extra resources.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Thus, most game designs through the 1980s were designed through a hard-coded rule set with a small number of levels and graphics data.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Since the golden age of arcade video games, it became common for video game companies to develop in-house game engines for use with first-party software.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] A notable example of an in-house game engine on home consoles in the mid-1980s was the smooth side-scrolling engine developed by Shigeru Miyamoto's team at Nintendo for the Nintendo Entertainment System (NES).
[src:game-dev/game-engine] The engine they had developed for the side-scrolling racing game *Excitebike* (1984) was later employed for the scrolling platformer *Super Mario Bros.* (1985).
[src:game-dev/game-engine] This allowed Mario to smoothly accelerate from a walk to a run, rather than move at a constant speed like in earlier platformers.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] While third-party game engines were not common until the rise of 3D computer graphics in the 1990s, several 2D game creation systems were produced in the 1980s for independent video game development.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Klik & Play (1994) is another legacy offering that is still available.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] The term *game engine* emerged in the mid-1990s, particularly with the rise of 3D games like first-person shooters, which often featured a dedicated first-person shooter engine.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] For instance, Epic Games, founded by Tim Sweeney, debuted its Unreal Engine in 1998.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Later games, such as id Software's *Quake III Arena* and Epic Games' *Unreal* (1998), were designed with this approach in mind, with the engine and content developed separately.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] At the very least, reusable engines make developing game sequels faster and easier, which is a valuable advantage in the competitive video game industry.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] While a strong rivalry existed between Epic Games and id Software around 2000, Epic Game's Unreal Engine has since become far more popular than id Tech 4 and its successor, id Tech 5.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Modern game engines are some of the most complex applications written, often featuring dozens of finely-tuned systems interacting to ensure a precisely-controlled user experience.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] The continued evolution of game engines has created a strong separation between rendering, scripting, artwork, and level design.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] As such, it is now common, for example, for a typical game development team to have several times as many artists as actual programmers.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] While third-party game engines are predominantly used in the development of first-person shooter games, they are also being used across other genres.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] For example, Gamebryo is used in *The Elder Scrolls III: Morrowind* and *Dark Age of Camelot*, whereas Unreal Engine 2 is used in *Lineage II*.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Game engines are also used for games originally developed for home consoles, with RenderWare for the *Grand Theft Auto* and *Burnout* franchises as an example.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Due to modern multi-core systems and growing demands in realism, exploiting threads has become more important.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Separate threads of execution within a game engine manage intensive operations, including rendering, asset streaming, audio playback, and physics simulation.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Racing games have typically been at the forefront of threading with the physics engine running in a separate thread long before other core subsystems were moved, partly because rendering and related tasks need updating at only 30–60 Hz.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] For example, on PlayStation 3, physics ran in *Need For Speed* at 100 Hz, versus *Forza Motorsport 2* at 360 Hz.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Although the term was first used in the 1990s, few earlier systems in 1980s are considered as game engines, such as Sierra's Adventure Game Interpreter (AGI) and SCI systems, LucasArts' SCUMM system and Incentive Software's Freescape engine (in 1986).
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Unlike most modern game engines, these game engines were never used in any third-party products (except for the SCUMM system, which was licensed to and used by Humongous Entertainment).
[src:game-dev/game-engine] As game engine technology matures and becomes more user friendly, the application of game engines has widened in scope.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] They are now used for serious games: visualization, training, medical, and military simulation applications, with the CryEngine being one example.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] To improve accessibility, new hardware platforms are also now targeted by game engines, including mobile phones (e.g.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Additionally, more game engines are being built upon higher-level languages, such as Java, C# and .NET (e.g., TorqueX, and Visual3D.NET), Python (Panda3D), or Lua Script (Leadwerks).
[src:game-dev/game-engine] As most 3D-rich games are now mostly limited by the power of a graphics card, the potential slowdown due to translation overheads of higher-level languages becomes negligible, while productivity gains offered by these languages serve the game engine developers' benefit.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] These recent trends are being propelled by companies such as Microsoft to support indie game development.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Microsoft developed XNA as the primary Software Development Kit (SDK) for all video games released on Xbox and their related products.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] This includes the Xbox Live Indie Games channel designed specifically for smaller developers who do not have the extensive resources necessary to box games for sale on retail shelves.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] It is becoming easier and cheaper than ever to develop game engines for platforms that support managed frameworks.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Producers of game engines decide how they allow users to use their products.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Just as gaming is an industry, so are the engines they are built off.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] The major game engines come at varying prices, whether it be in the form of subscription fees or license payments.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Unity and Unreal Engine are currently the two most popular choices for game developers.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Although the differences among the different game engines blur as they build their own tools on top of them, different game developers may be too used to a system to change, or attracted by the huge benefits of such engines regardless of pay-walls.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Free and open-source engines such as Godot, have seen a rise in popularity, particularly following the 2023 Unity pricing controversy which drove game developers and studios to seek engines with a permissive license.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Applied more broadly, game engines themselves can be described as middleware.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] In video games, however, *middleware* is often used to refer to subsystems of functionality within a game engine.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Some game middleware does only one thing, yet does it more convincingly or more efficiently than general purpose middleware.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] The four most-widely used middleware packages that provide subsystems of functionality include RAD Game Tools' Bink, Firelight FMOD, Havok, and Scaleform GFx.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] RAD Game Tools develops Bink for basic video rendering, along with Miles audio, and Granny 3D rendering.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Firelight FMOD is a low cost robust audio library and toolset.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Havok provides a robust physics simulation system, along with a suite of animation and behavior applications.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Scaleform provides GFx for high performance Flash UI and high-quality video playback, and an Input Method Editor (IME) addon for in-game Asian chat support.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Other middleware is used for performance optimization—for example Simplygon helps to optimize and generate level of detail meshes, and Umbra adds occlusion culling optimizations to 3D graphics.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Some middleware contains full source code, or is provided an API reference for a compiled binary library.
[src:game-dev/game-engine] Some middleware programs can be licensed either way, usually for a higher fee for full source code.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Pathfinding is closely related to the shortest path problem, within graph theory, which examines how to identify the path that best meets some criteria (shortest, cheapest, fastest, etc) between two points in a large network.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] At its core, a pathfinding method searches a graph by starting at one vertex and exploring adjacent nodes until the destination node is reached, generally with the intent of finding the cheapest route.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Although graph searching methods such as a breadth-first search would find a route if given enough time, other methods, which "explore" the graph, would tend to reach the destination sooner.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] An analogy would be a person walking across a room; rather than examining every possible route in advance, the person would generally walk in the direction of the destination and only deviate from the path to avoid an obstruction, and make deviations as minor as possible.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Two primary problems of pathfinding are (1) to find a path between two nodes in a graph; and (2) the shortest path problem—to find the optimal shortest path.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Basic algorithms such as breadth-first and depth-first search address the first problem by exhausting all possibilities; starting from the given node, they iterate over all potential paths until they reach the destination node.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] These algorithms run in $O(|V|+|E|)$ , or linear time, where V is the number of vertices, and E is the number of edges between vertices.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] The more complicated problem is finding the optimal path.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] The exhaustive approach in this case is known as the Bellman–Ford algorithm, which yields a time complexity of $O(|V||E|)$ , or quadratic time.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] However, it is not necessary to examine all possible paths to find the optimal one.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Algorithms such as A* and Dijkstra's algorithm strategically eliminate paths, either through heuristics or through dynamic programming.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] By eliminating impossible paths, these algorithms can achieve time complexities as low as $O(|E|\log(|V|))$ .
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] The above algorithms are among the best general algorithms which operate on a graph without preprocessing.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] However, in practical travel-routing systems, even better time complexities can be attained by algorithms which can pre-process the graph to attain better performance.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] One such algorithm is contraction hierarchies.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A common example of a graph-based pathfinding algorithm is Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] This algorithm begins with a start node and an "open set" of candidate nodes.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] At each step, the node in the open set with the lowest distance from the start is examined.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] The node is marked "closed", and all nodes adjacent to it are added to the open set if they have not already been examined.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] This process repeats until a path to the destination has been found.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Since the lowest distance nodes are examined first, the first time the destination is found, the path to it will be the shortest path.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Dijkstra's algorithm fails if there is a negative edge weight.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] In the hypothetical situation where Nodes A, B, and C form a connected undirected graph with edges AB = 3, AC = 4, and BC = −2, the optimal path from A to C costs 1, and the optimal path from A to B costs 2.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Dijkstra's Algorithm starting from A will first examine B, as that is the closest.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] It will assign a cost of 3 to it, and mark it closed, meaning that its cost will never be reevaluated.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Therefore, Dijkstra's cannot evaluate negative edge weights.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] However, since for many practical purposes there will never be a negative edgeweight, Dijkstra's algorithm is largely suitable for the purpose of pathfinding.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A* is a variant of Dijkstra's algorithm with a wide variety of use cases.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A* assigns a weight to each open node equal to the weight of the edge to that node plus the approximate distance between that node and the finish.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] This approximate distance is found by the heuristic, and represents a minimum possible distance between that node and the end.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] This allows it to eliminate longer paths once an initial path is found.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] If there is a path of length x between the start and finish, and the minimum distance between a node and the finish is greater than x, that node need not be examined.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A* uses this heuristic to improve on the behavior relative to Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] When the heuristic evaluates to zero, A* is equivalent to Dijkstra's algorithm.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] As the heuristic estimate increases and gets closer to the true distance, A* continues to find optimal paths, but runs faster (by virtue of examining fewer nodes).
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] When the value of the heuristic is exactly the true distance, A* examines the fewest nodes.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] In many applications (such as video games) this is acceptable and even desirable, in order to keep the algorithm running quickly.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Pathfinding has a history of being included in video games with moving objects or NPCs.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Chris Crawford in 1982 described how he "expended a great deal of time" trying to solve a problem with pathfinding in *Tanktics*, in which computer tanks became trapped on land within U-shaped lakes.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] "After much wasted effort I discovered a better solution: delete U-shaped lakes from the map", he said.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] The concept of hierarchical pathfinding predates its adoption by the video game industry and has its roots in classical artificial intelligence research.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] One of the earliest formal descriptions appears in Sacerdoti's work on ABSTRIPS (Abstraction-Based STRIPS) in 1974, which explored hierarchical search strategies in logic-based planning.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Later research, such as Hierarchical A* by Holte et al., further developed the theory of abstraction hierarchies in search problems.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] In the context of video games, the need for efficient planning on large maps with limited CPU time led to the practical implementation of hierarchical pathfinding algorithms.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A notable advancement was the introduction of Hierarchical Path-Finding A* (HPA*) by Botea et al. in 2004.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] HPA* partitions the map into clusters and precomputes optimal local paths between entrance points of adjacent clusters.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] At runtime, it plans an abstract path through the cluster graph, then refines that path within each cluster.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] This significantly reduces the search space and allows for near-optimal planning with much faster performance.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Partial-Refinement A* (PRA*), developed by Sturtevant and Buro, takes a similar approach but emphasizes interleaved planning and acting.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Instead of refining the entire path immediately, PRA* refines only the first few steps and continues refining the rest as needed during execution.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] This is especially useful in dynamic environments.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Similar techniques include navigation meshes (navmesh), used for geometric planning in games, and multimodal transportation planning, such as in variations of the travelling salesman problem that involve multiple transport types.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A hierarchical planner performs pathfinding in two phases: first, between clusters at a high level; then, within individual clusters at a low level.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] This structure enables guided local search with fewer nodes, resulting in high performance.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] The main drawback is the implementation complexity of maintaining abstraction layers and refinements.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A map with a size of 3000×2000 nodes contains 6 million tiles.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Planning a path directly on this scale, even with an optimized algorithm, is computationally intensive due to the vast number of graph nodes and possible paths.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A hierarchical approach divides the map into 300×200 node clusters, forming a 10×10 grid (100 clusters total).
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] The high-level abstract graph now contains only 100 nodes.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A path is planned between these clusters, which is computationally cheap.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Once the abstract path is found, each cluster on the path is processed using a regular A* planner to find the exact low-level route within.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] This two-stage process significantly improves efficiency while maintaining near-optimal path quality.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Multi-agent pathfinding is to find the paths for multiple agents from their current locations to their target locations without colliding with each other, while at the same time optimizing a cost function, such as the sum of the path lengths of all agents.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Many multi-agent pathfinding algorithms are generalized from A*, or based on reduction to other well studied problems such as integer linear programming.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] However, such algorithms are typically incomplete; in other words, not proven to produce a solution within polynomial time.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] Some parallel approaches, such as Collaborative Diffusion, are based on embarrassingly parallel algorithms spreading multi-agent pathfinding into computational grid structures, e.g., cells similar to cellular automata.
[src:game-dev/pathfinding] A different category of algorithms sacrifice optimality for performance by either making use of known navigation patterns (such as traffic flow) or the topology of the problem space.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] A **physics engine** is computer software that provides an approximate simulation of certain physical systems, typically classical dynamics, including rigid body dynamics (including collision detection), soft body dynamics, and fluid dynamics.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] It is of use in the domains of computer graphics, video games and film (CGI).
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Their main uses are in video games (typically as middleware), in which case the simulations are in real-time.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The term is sometimes used more generally to describe any software system for simulating physical phenomena, such as high-performance scientific simulation.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] There are generally two classes of physics engines: real-time and high-precision.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] High-precision physics engines require more processing power to calculate very precise physics and are usually used by scientists and prerendered computer animation, such as movies.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Real-time physics engines—as used in video games and other forms of interactive computing—use simplified calculations and decreased accuracy to compute in time for the game to respond at an appropriate rate for game play.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] A physics engine is essentially a big calculator that does mathematics needed to simulate physics.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] One of the first general purpose computers, ENIAC, was used as a very simple type of physics engine.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] It was used to design ballistics tables to help the United States military estimate where artillery shells of various mass would land when fired at varying angles and gunpowder charges, also accounting for drift caused by wind.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The results were calculated a single time only, and were tabulated into printed tables handed out to the artillery commanders.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Physics engines have been commonly used on supercomputers since the 1980s to perform computational fluid dynamics modeling, where particles are assigned force vectors that are combined to show circulation.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Due to the requirements of speed and high precision, special computer processors known as vector processors were developed to accelerate the calculations.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The techniques can be used to model weather patterns in weather forecasting, wind tunnel data for designing air- and watercraft or motor vehicles including racecars, and thermal cooling of computer processors for improving heat sinks.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] As with many calculation-laden processes in computing, the accuracy of the simulation is related to the resolution of the simulation and the precision of the calculations; small fluctuations not modeled in the simulation can drastically change the predicted results.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Tire manufacturers use physics simulations to examine how new tire tread types will perform under wet and dry conditions, using new tire materials of varying flexibility and under different levels of weight loading.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The simulations optimize tire operations, material selection, costs, and enhance time efficiency.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] In most computer games, speed of the processors and gameplay are more important than accuracy of simulation.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] This leads to designs for physics engines that produce results in real-time but that replicate real world physics only for simple cases and typically with some approximation.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] More often than not, the simulation is geared towards providing a "perceptually correct" approximation rather than a real simulation.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] However some game engines, such as Source, use physics in puzzles or in combat situations.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] This requires more accurate physics so that, for example, the momentum of an object can knock over an obstacle or lift a sinking object.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Physically-based character animation in the past only used rigid body dynamics because they are faster and easier to calculate, but modern games and movies are starting to use soft body physics.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Soft body physics are also used for particle effects, liquids and cloth.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Some form of limited fluid dynamics simulation is sometimes provided to simulate water and other liquids as well as the flow of fire and explosions through the air.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Objects in games interact with the player, the environment, and each other.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Typically, most 3D objects in games are represented by two separate meshes or shapes.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] One of these meshes is the highly complex and detailed shape visible to the player in the game, such as a vase with elegant curved and looping handles.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] For purpose of speed, a second, simplified invisible mesh is used to represent the object to the physics engine so that the physics engine treats the example vase as a simple cylinder.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] It would thus be impossible to insert a rod or fire a projectile through the handle holes on the vase, because the physics engine model is based on the cylinder and is unaware of the handles.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The simplified mesh used for physics processing is often referred to as the collision geometry.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] This may be a bounding box, sphere, or convex hull.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Engines that use bounding boxes or bounding spheres as the final shape for collision detection are considered extremely simple.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Generally a bounding box is used for broad phase collision detection to narrow down the number of possible collisions before costly mesh on mesh collision detection is done in the narrow phase of collision detection.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Another aspect of precision in discrete collision detection involves the framerate, or the number of moments in time per second when physics is calculated.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Each frame is treated as separate from all other frames, and the space between frames is not calculated.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] A low framerate and a small fast-moving object causes a situation where the object does not move smoothly through space but instead seems to teleport from one point in space to the next as each frame is calculated.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Projectiles moving at sufficiently high speeds will miss targets, if the target is small enough to fit in the gap between the calculated frames of the fast moving projectile.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Various techniques are used to overcome this flaw, such as *Second Life*'s representation of projectiles as arrows with invisible trailing tails longer than the gap in frames to collide with any object that might fit between the calculated frames.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] By contrast, continuous collision detection such as in Bullet or Havok does not suffer this problem.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] An alternative to using bounding box-based rigid body physics systems is to use a finite element-based system.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] In such a system, a 3-dimensional, volumetric tessellation is created of the 3D object.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The tessellation results in a number of finite elements which represent aspects of the object's physical properties such as toughness, plasticity, and volume preservation.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Once constructed, the finite elements are used by a solver to model the stress within the 3D object.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The stress can be used to drive fracture, deformation and other physical effects with a high degree of realism and uniqueness.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] As the number of modeled elements is increased, the engine's ability to model physical behavior increases.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The visual representation of the 3D object is altered by the finite element system through the use of a deformation shader run on the CPU or GPU.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Finite Element-based systems had been impractical for use in games due to the performance overhead and the lack of tools to create finite element representations out of 3D art objects.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] James O'Brien as a part of his PhD thesis.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] In the real world, physics is always active.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] There is a constant Brownian motion jitter to all particles in our universe as the forces push back and forth against each other.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] For a game physics engine, such constant active precision is unnecessarily wasting the limited CPU power, which can cause problems such as decreased framerate.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Thus, games may put objects to "sleep" by disabling the computation of physics on objects that have not moved a particular distance within a certain amount of time.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] For example, in the 3D virtual world Second Life, if an object is resting on the floor and the object does not move beyond a minimal distance in about two seconds, then the physics calculations are disabled for the object and it becomes frozen in place.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The object remains frozen until physics processing reactivates for the object after collision occurs with some other active physical object.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Physics engines for video games typically have two core components, a collision detection/collision response system, and the dynamics simulation component responsible for solving the forces affecting the simulated objects.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Modern physics engines may also contain fluid simulations, animation control systems and asset integration tools.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Finally, hybrid methods are possible that combine aspects of the above paradigms.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] A primary limit of physics engine realism is the approximated result of the constraint resolutions and collision result due to the slow convergence of algorithms.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Collision detection computed at a too low frequency can result in objects passing through each other and then being repelled with an abnormal correction force.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] On the other hand, approximated results of reaction force is due to the slow convergence of typical Projected Gauss Seidel solver resulting in abnormal bouncing.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Any type of free-moving compound physics object can demonstrate this problem, but it is especially prone to affecting chain links under high tension, and wheeled objects with actively physical bearing surfaces.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Higher precision reduces the positional/force errors, but at the cost of needing greater CPU power for the calculations.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] A physics processing unit (PPU) is a dedicated microprocessor designed to handle the calculations of physics, especially in the physics engine of video games.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Examples of calculations involving a PPU might include rigid body dynamics, soft body dynamics, collision detection, fluid dynamics, hair and clothing simulation, finite element analysis, and fracturing of objects.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The idea is that specialized processors offload time-consuming tasks from a computer's CPU, much like how a GPU performs graphics operations in the main CPU's place.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] The term was coined by Ageia's marketing to describe their PhysX chip to consumers.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Several other technologies in the CPU-GPU spectrum have some features in common with it, although Ageia's solution was the only complete one designed, marketed, supported, and placed within a system *exclusively* as a PPU.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] Hardware acceleration for physics processing is now usually provided by graphics processing units that support more general computation, a concept known as general-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU).
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] AMD and NVIDIA provide support for rigid body dynamics computations on their latest graphics cards.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] NVIDIA's GeForce 8 series supports a GPU-based Newtonian physics acceleration technology named *Quantum Effects Technology*.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] NVIDIA provides an SDK Toolkit for CUDA (Compute Unified Device Architecture) technology that offers both a low and high-level API to the GPU.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] For their GPUs, AMD offers a similar SDK, called Close to Metal (CTM), which provides a thin hardware interface.
[src:game-dev/physics-engine] PhysX is an example of a physics engine that can use GPGPU based hardware acceleration when it is available.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] In computing, **procedural generation** is a method of creating data algorithmically as opposed to manually, typically through a combination of human-generated content and algorithms coupled with computer-generated randomness and processing power.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] In computer graphics, it is commonly used to create textures and 3D models.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] In video games, it is used to automatically create large amounts of content in a game.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Depending on the implementation, advantages of procedural generation can include smaller file sizes, larger amounts of content, and randomness for less predictable gameplay.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] The term *procedural* refers to the process that computes a particular function.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Fractals are geometric patterns which can often be generated procedurally.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Commonplace procedural content includes textures and meshes.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Sound is often also procedurally generated, and has applications in both speech synthesis as well as music.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] It has been used to create compositions in various genres of electronic music by artists such as Brian Eno who popularized the term "generative music".
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Procedural generation was originally created as an instrument for video games, aiding in generating levels, textures and complete worlds with little human contribution.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Procedurally generated elements have appeared in video games since the 1990s: *The Elder Scrolls II: Daggerfall* takes place in a mostly procedurally generated world, giving a world roughly two thirds the actual size of the British Isles.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] *Soldier of Fortune* from Raven Software uses simple routines to detail enemy models, while its sequel featured a randomly generated level mode.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Avalanche Studios employed procedural generation to create a large and varied group of detailed tropical islands for *Just Cause*.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] *No Man's Sky*, a game developed by games studio Hello Games, is all based upon procedurally generated elements.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] The modern demoscene uses procedural generation to package a great deal of audiovisual content into relatively small programs.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] New methods and applications are presented annually in conferences such as the IEEE Conference on Computational Intelligence and Games and the AAAI Conference on Artificial Intelligence and Interactive Digital Entertainment.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Particularly in the application of procedural generation with video games, which are intended to be highly replayable, there are concerns that procedural systems can generate infinite numbers of worlds to explore, but without sufficient human guidance and rules to guide these.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Using procedural generation in games had origins in tabletop role playing games (RPG).
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] The leading tabletop system, *Advanced Dungeons & Dragons*, provided ways for the "dungeon master" to generate dungeons and terrain using random die rolls, expanded in later editions with complex branching procedural tables.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Strategic Simulations under license from TSR released the *Dungeon Master's Assistant*, a computer program that generated dungeons based on these published tables.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] *Tunnels & Trolls*, published by Flying Buffalo, was designed primarily around solitary play and used similar procedural generation for its dungeons.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Other tabletop RPGs borrowed similar concepts in procedural generation for various world elements.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Many online tools for Dungeon Masters now use procedural generation to varying degrees.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Prior to graphically oriented video games, roguelike games, a genre directly inspired by *Dungeons & Dragons* adopted for solitary play, heavily utilized procedural generation to randomly produce dungeons, in the same manner that tabletop systems had done.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Such early games include *Beneath Apple Manor* (1978) and the genre's namesake, *Rogue* (1980).
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] The procedural generation system in roguelikes would create dungeons in ASCII- or regular tile-based systems and define rooms, hallways, monsters, and treasure to challenge the player.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Roguelikes, and games based on the roguelike concepts, allow the development of complex gameplay without having to spend excessive time in creating a game's world.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] 1978's *Maze Craze* for the Atari VCS used an algorithm to generate a random, top-down maze for each game.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Some games used pseudorandom number generators.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] These PRNGs were often used with predefined seed values in order to generate very large game worlds that appeared to be premade.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] *The Sentinel* supposedly had 10,000 different levels stored in only 48 and 64 kilobytes.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] An extreme case was *Elite*, which was originally planned to contain a total of 248 (approximately 282 trillion) galaxies with 256 solar systems each.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] However, the publisher was afraid that such a gigantic universe would cause disbelief in players, and eight of these galaxies were chosen for the final version.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Though modern computer games do not have the same memory and hardware restrictions that earlier games had, the use of procedural generation is frequently employed to create randomized games, maps, levels, characters, or other facets that are unique on each playthrough.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] This also extends to power-ups and other items that populate the game's map, selected by the game through procedural generational rules to assure the game feels fair to the player so they feel they have the agency to win the game.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Procedural generation is often used in loot systems of quest-driven games, such as action role-playing games and massive multiplayer online role playing games.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Though quests may feature fixed rewards, other loot, such as weapons and armor, may be generated for the player based on the player-character's level, the quest's level, their performance in the quest, and other random factors.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] This often leads to loot having a rarity quality applied to reflect when the procedural generation system has produced an item with better-than-average attributes.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] For example, the *Borderlands* series is based on its procedural generation system which can create over a million unique guns and other equipment.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Many open world or survival games procedurally create a game world from a random seed or one provided by the player, so that each playthrough is different.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] These generation systems create numerous pixel- or voxel-based biomes with distribution of resources, objects, and creatures.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] The player frequently has the ability to adjust some of the generation parameters, such as specifying the amount of water coverage in a world.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Procedural generation is also used in space exploration and trading games.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] *Elite: Dangerous*, through using the 400 billion known stars of the Milky Way Galaxy as its world basis, uses procedural generation to simulate the planets in these solar systems.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Similarly, *Star Citizen* uses the technology to create seamlessly loaded planets among its hand-crafted universe.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] *Outerra Anteworld* is a video game in development that uses procedural generation and real world data to create a virtual replica of planet Earth in true scale.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] As in video games, procedural generation is often used in film to create visually interesting and accurate spaces rapidly.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] This comes in a wide variety of applications.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] One application is *imperfect factories*, which are used by artists to rapidly generate many similar objects.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] This accounts for the fact that, in real life, no two objects are ever exactly alike.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] For instance, an artist can model a product for a grocery store, and then create an imperfect factory to generate many imperfect copies to populate a whole shelf.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] MASSIVE is a high-end computer animation and artificial intelligence software package used for generating crowd-related visual effects for film and television.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] It was developed to create fighting armies of hundreds of thousands of soldiers for Peter Jackson's *The Lord of the Rings* films automatically.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Coherent noise can be extremely important to procedural workflow in film.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Simplex noise is often faster with fewer artifacts, though an older function called Perlin noise may be used as well.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Coherent noise, in this case, refers to a function that generates smooth pseudo-randomness in *n* dimensions.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Poyck studied how procedurally generated cityscapes can be used to aid social simulations and to train self-driving cars.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Procedural generation plays a pivotal part in the progression of digital twins, which are very detailed virtual replicas of real-world objects used for simulation, analysis, and planning.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Neural networks have recently been employed to refine procedurally generated content.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Combining classic randomization methods with deep learning provides new ways for generating audio, images, 3D objects, and other content types.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] This is especially useful in game level development; reinforcement learning allows the development of agents that play generated levels, serving as automatic content evaluators.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Integrating procedural generation with deep learning alters the landscape of digital content creation.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Zakaria et al. demonstrated that different deep learning methods for procedurally generating Sokoban levels have different strengths and weaknesses.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Looking ahead, researchers are investigating methods to combine large language models (LLMs) with deep-learning powered procedural generation systems, aiming to enhance their adaptability.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Zakaria suggests that "LLMs combined with reinforcement learning can create procedural assets that evolve dynamically based on real-time feedback".
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] Zakaria investigated the application of advanced deep learning structures such as bootstrapped LSTM (Long short-term memory) generators and GANs (Generative adversarial networks) to upgrade procedural level design.
[src:game-dev/procedural-generation] They found that "diversity sampling consistently increases the numbers of generated solutions and signatures", showing that hybrid approaches help overcome problems like repetitive patterns or lack of variation.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] In computer graphics, a **sprite** is a two-dimensional bitmap that is integrated into a larger scene, most often in a 2D video game.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Originally, the term *sprite* referred to fixed-sized objects composited together, by hardware, with a background.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Use of the term has since become more general.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware varies in the number of sprites supported, the size and colors of each sprite, and special effects such as scaling or reporting pixel-precise overlap.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware composition of sprites occurs as each scan line is prepared for the video output device, such as a cathode-ray tube, without involvement of the main CPU and without the need for a full-screen frame buffer.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites can be positioned or altered by setting attributes used during the hardware composition process.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The number of sprites which can be displayed per scan line is often lower than the total number of sprites a system supports.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] For example, the Texas Instruments TMS9918 chip supports 32 sprites, but only four can appear on the same scan line.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The CPUs in modern computers, video game consoles, and mobile devices are fast enough that bitmaps can be drawn into a frame buffer without special hardware assistance.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Beyond that, GPUs can render vast numbers of scaled, rotated, anti-aliased, partially translucent, very high resolution images in parallel with the CPU.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Karl Guttag, one of two engineers for the 1979 Texas Instruments TMS9918 video display processor, this use of the word *sprite* came from David Ackley, a manager at TI.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] It was also used by Danny Hillis at Texas Instruments in the late 1970s.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The term was derived from the fact that sprites "float" on top of the background image without overwriting it, much like a ghost or mythological sprite.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The use of sprites originated with arcade video games.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Nolan Bushnell came up with the original concept when he developed the first arcade video game, *Computer Space* (1971).
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Technical limitations made it difficult to adapt the early mainframe game *Spacewar!* (1962), which performed an entire screen refresh for every little movement, so he came up with a solution to the problem: controlling each individual game element with a dedicated transistor.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The rockets were essentially hardwired bitmaps that moved around the screen independently of the background, an important innovation for producing screen images more efficiently and providing the basis for sprite graphics.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The earliest video games to represent player characters as human player sprites were arcade sports video games, beginning with Taito's *TV Basketball*, released in April 1974 and licensed to Midway Manufacturing for release in North America.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Designed by Tomohiro Nishikado, he wanted to move beyond simple *Pong*-style rectangles to character graphics, by rearranging the rectangle shapes into objects that look like basketball players and basketball hoops.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Ramtek released another sports video game in October 1974, *Baseball*, which similarly displayed human-like characters.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The Namco Galaxian arcade system board, for the 1979 arcade game *Galaxian*, displays animated, multi-colored sprites over a scrolling background.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] It became the basis for Nintendo's *Radar Scope* and *Donkey Kong* arcade hardware and home consoles such as the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] According to Steve Golson from General Computer Corporation, the term "stamp" was used instead of "sprite" at the time.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Signetics devised the first chips capable of generating sprite graphics (referred to as *objects* by Signetics) for home systems.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The Signetics 2636 video processors were first used in the 1978 1292 Advanced Programmable Video System and later in the 1979 Elektor TV Games Computer.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The Atari VCS, released in 1977, has a hardware sprite implementation where five graphical objects can be moved independently of the game playfield.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The term *sprite* was not in use at the time.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The VCS's sprites are called *movable objects* in the programming manual, further identified as two *players*, two *missiles*, and one *ball*.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] These each consist of a single row of pixels that are displayed on a scan line.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] To produce a two-dimensional shape, the sprite's single-row bitmap is altered by software from one scan line to the next.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The 1979 Atari 400 and 800 home computers have similar, but more elaborate, circuitry capable of moving eight single-color objects per scan line: four 8-bit wide *players* and four 2-bit wide *missiles*.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Each is the full height of the display—a long, thin strip.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] DMA from a table in memory automatically sets the graphics pattern registers for each scan line.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Hardware registers control the horizontal position of each player and missile.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Vertical motion is achieved by moving the bitmap data within a player or missile's strip.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] The feature was called *player/missile graphics* by Atari.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Texas Instruments developed the TMS9918 chip with sprite support for its 1979 TI-99/4 home computer.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] An updated version is used in the 1981 TI-99/4A.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remained popular with the rise of 2.5D games (those which recreate a 3D game space from a 2D map) in the late 1980s and early 1990s.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] A technique called billboarding allows 2.5D games to keep onscreen sprites rotated toward the player view at all times.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Some 2.5D games, such as 1993's *Doom*, allow the same entity to be represented by different sprites depending on its rotation relative to the viewer, furthering the illusion of 3D.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Fully 3D games usually present world objects as 3D models, but sprites are supported in some 3D game engines, such as GoldSrc and Unreal, and may be billboarded or locked to fixed orientations.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] Sprites remain useful for small details, particle effects, and other applications where the lack of a third dimension is not a major detriment.
[src:game-dev/sprite-computer-graphics] These are base hardware specs and do not include additional programming techniques, such as using raster interrupts to repurpose sprites mid-frame.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Development of commercial video games is normally funded by a publisher and can take two to five years to reach completion.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Game creation by small, self-funded teams is called independent development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The technology in a game may be written from scratch or use proprietary software specific to one company.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] As development has become more complex, it has become common for companies and independent developers alike to use off-the-shelf "engines" such as Unity, Unreal Engine or Godot.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Commercial game development began in the 1970s with the advent of arcade video games, first-generation video game consoles like the Atari 2600, and home computers like the Apple II.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Into the 1980s, a lone programmer could develop a full and complete game such as *Pitfall!*.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] By the second and third generation of video game consoles in the late 1980s, the growing popularity of 3D graphics on personal computers meant higher expectations for visuals and quality, making it difficult for a single person to produce a mainstream video game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The average cost of producing a high-end (often called AAA) game slowly rose from US$1–4 million in 2000, to over $200 million and up by 2023.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] At the same time, independent game development has flourished.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The best-selling video game of all time, *Minecraft*, was initially written by one person before it gained traction.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Mojang was founded to develop it, and it was eventually acquired by Microsoft and greatly expanded.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Mainstream commercial video games are generally developed in phases.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A concept is developed which then moves to pre-production where prototypes are written and the plan for the entire game is created.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] This is followed by full-scale development or *production*, then sometimes a post-production period where the game is polished.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] It has become common for many developers, especially smaller developers, to publicly release games in an "early access" form, where iterative development takes place in tandem with feedback from actual players.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Games are produced through the software development process.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] They are created both as a form of artistic expression and a commercial product intended to generate profit.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Game development is often described as a blend of art and science, reflecting the technical precision and creative design required.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Development is normally funded by a publisher, and careful budget estimation is critical to success.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Poor planning may cause projects to exceed budgets or fail to meet expectations.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In fact, the majority of commercial games do not produce profit.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Most developers therefore plan their production schedule carefully to balance creative goals with available resources.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The game industry requires innovations, as publishers cannot profit from the constant release of repetitive sequels and imitations.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Every year new independent development companies open and some manage to develop hit titles.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Similarly, many developers close down because they cannot find a publishing contract or their production is not profitable.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] It is difficult to start a new company due to the high initial investment required.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Nevertheless, the growth of the casual and mobile game market has allowed developers with smaller teams to enter the market.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Once the companies become financially stable, they may expand to develop larger games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Most developers start small and gradually expand their business.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A developer receiving profit from a successful title may store up capital to expand and re-factor their company, as well as tolerate more failed deadlines.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] An average development budget for a multiplatform game is US$18-28M, with high-profile games often exceeding $40M.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In the early era of home computers and video game consoles in the early 1980s, a single programmer could handle almost all the tasks of developing a game — programming, graphical design, sound effects, etc.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] It could take as little as six weeks to develop a game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] However, the high user expectations and requirements of modern commercial games far exceed the capabilities of a single developer and require the splitting of responsibilities.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A team of over a hundred people can be employed full-time for a single project.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Game development, production, or design is a process that starts from an idea or concept.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Often the idea is based on a modification of an existing game concept.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The game idea may fall within one or several genres.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Designers often experiment with different combinations of genres.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A game designer generally writes an initial game proposal document, that describes the basic concept, gameplay, feature list, setting and story, target audience, requirements and schedule, and finally staff and budget estimates.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Different companies have different formal procedures and philosophies regarding game design and development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] There is no standardized development method; however commonalities exist.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A game developer may range from a single individual to a large multinational company.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] There are both independent and publisher-owned studios.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Independent developers rely on financial support from a game publisher.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] They usually have to develop a game from concept to prototype without external funding.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The formal game proposal is then submitted to publishers, who may finance the game development from several months to years.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The publisher would retain exclusive rights to distribute and market the game and would often own the intellectual property rights for the game franchise.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The publisher may also own the development studio, or it may have internal development studio(s).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Generally the publisher is the one who owns the game's intellectual property rights.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Many larger development companies work on several titles at once.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] This is necessary because of the time taken between shipping a game and receiving royalty payments, which may be between 6 and 18 months.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Small companies may structure contracts, ask for advances on royalties, use shareware distribution, employ part-time workers and use other methods to meet payroll demands.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Console manufacturers, such as Microsoft, Nintendo, or Sony, have a standard set of technical requirements that a game must conform to in order to be approved.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Additionally, the game concept must be approved by the manufacturer, who may refuse to approve certain titles.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Most modern PC or console games take from three to five years to complete, whereas a mobile game can be developed in a few months.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The length of development is influenced by a number of factors, such as genre, scale, development platform and number of assets.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Some games can take much longer than the average time frame to complete.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] An infamous example is 3D Realms' *Duke Nukem Forever*, announced to be in production in April 1997 and released fourteen years later in June 2011.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Planning for Maxis' game *Spore* began in late 1999; the game was released nine years later in September 2008.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The game *Prey* was briefly profiled in a 1997 issue of PC Gamer, but was not released until 2006, and only then in highly altered form.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Finally, *Team Fortress 2* was in development from 1998 until its 2007 release, and emerged from a convoluted development process involving "probably three or four different games", according to Gabe Newell.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The game revenue from retail is divided among the parties along the distribution chain, such as — developer, publisher, retail, manufacturer and console royalty.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Many developers fail to profit from this and go bankrupt.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Many seek alternative economic models through Internet marketing and distribution channels to improve returns, as through a mobile distribution channel the share of a developer can be up to 70% of the total revenue and through an online distribution channel owned by the developer almost 100%.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The history of game making begins with the development of the first video games, although which video game is the first depends on the definition of *video game*.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The first games created had little entertainment value, and their development focus was separate from user experience—in fact, these games required mainframe computers to play them.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Douglas in 1952, was the first computer game to use a digital display.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 1958, a game called *Tennis for Two*, which displayed its output on an oscilloscope, was made by Willy Higinbotham, a physicist working at the Brookhaven National Laboratory.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 1961, a mainframe computer game called *Spacewar!* was developed by a group of Massachusetts Institute of Technology students led by Steve Russell.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] True commercial design and development of games began in the 1970s, when arcade video games and first-generation consoles were marketed.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 1971, *Computer Space* was the first commercially sold, coin-operated video game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] It used a black-and-white television for its display, and the computer system was made of 74 series TTL chips.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 1972, the first home console system was released called Magnavox Odyssey, developed by Ralph H.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] That same year, Atari released *Pong*, an arcade game that increased video game popularity.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The commercial success of *Pong* led other companies to develop *Pong* clones, spawning the video game industry.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Programmers worked within the big companies to produce games for these devices.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The industry did not see huge innovation in game design and a large number of consoles had very similar games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Many of these early games were often *Pong* clones.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Some games were different, however, such as *Gun Fight*, which was significant for several reasons: an early 1975 on-foot, multi-directional shooter, which depicted game characters, game violence, and human-to-human combat.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Tomohiro Nishikado's original version was based on discrete logic, which Dave Nutting adapted using the Intel 8080, making it the first video game to use a microprocessor.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Console manufacturers soon started to produce consoles that were able to play independently developed games, and ran on microprocessors, marking the beginning of second-generation consoles, beginning with the release of the Fairchild Channel F in 1976.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The flood of *Pong* clones led to the video game crash of 1977, which eventually came to an end with the mainstream success of Taito's 1978 arcade shooter game *Space Invaders*, marking the beginning of the golden age of arcade video games and inspiring dozens of manufacturers to enter the market.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Its creator Nishikado not only designed and programmed the game, but also did the artwork, engineered the arcade hardware, and put together a microcomputer from scratch.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] It was soon ported to the Atari 2600, becoming the first "killer app" and quadrupling the console's sales.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] At the same time, home computers appeared on the market, allowing individual programmers and hobbyists to develop games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] This allowed hardware manufacturer and software manufacturers to act separately.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A very large number of games could be produced by an individual, as games were easy to make because graphical and memory limitation did not allow for much content.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Larger companies developed, who focused selected teams to work on a title.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The developers of many early home video games, such as *Zork*, *Baseball*, *Air Warrior*, and *Adventure*, later transitioned their work as products of the early video game industry.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The industry expanded significantly at the time, with the arcade video game sector alone (representing the largest share of the gaming industry) generating higher revenues than both pop music and Hollywood films combined.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The home video game industry, however, suffered major losses following the video game crash of 1983.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Chris Crawford and Don Daglow in 1987 similarly advised prospective designers to write games as a hobby first, and to not quit their existing jobs early.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The home video game industry was revitalized soon after by the widespread success of the Nintendo Entertainment System.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2000 a 12 to 36 month development project was funded by a publisher for US$1M–3M.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Additionally, $250k–1.5M were spent on marketing and sales development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2001, over 3000 games were released for PC; and from about 100 games turning profit only about 50 made significant profit.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In the early 2000s it became increasingly common to use middleware game engines, such as *Quake* engine or Unreal Engine.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In the early 2000s, also mobile games started to gain popularity.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] However, mobile games distributed by mobile operators remained a marginal form of gaming until the Apple App Store was launched in 2008.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2005, a mainstream console video game cost from US$3M to $6M to develop.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Some games cost as much as $20M to develop.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2006 the profit from a console game sold at retail was divided among parties of distribution chain as follows: developer (13%), publisher (32%), retail (32%), manufacturer (5%), console royalty (18%).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2008 a developer would retain around 17% of retail price and around 85% if sold online.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Since the third generation of consoles, the home video game industry has constantly increased and expanded.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The industry revenue has increased at least five-fold since the 1990s.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2007, the software portion of video game revenue was $9.5 billion, exceeding that of the movie industry.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The Apple App Store, introduced in 2008, was the first mobile application store operated directly by the mobile-platform holder.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] It significantly changed the consumer behaviour more favourable for downloading mobile content and quickly broadened the markets of mobile games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2009 games' market annual value was estimated between $7–30 billion, depending on which sales figures are included.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] This is on par with films' box office market.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A publisher would typically fund an independent developer for $500k–$5M for a development of a title.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2012, the total value had already reached $66.3 billion and by then the video game markets were no longer dominated by console games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] According to Newzoo, the share of MMO's was 19.8%, PC/MAC's 9.8%, tablets' 3.2%, smartphones 10.6%, handhelds' 9.8%, consoles' only 36.7% and online casual games 10.2%.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The fastest growing market segments being mobile games with an average annual rate of 19% for smartphones and 48% for tablets.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In the past several years, many developers opened and many closed down.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Each year a number of developers are acquired by larger companies or merge with existing companies.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] For example, in 2007 Blizzard Entertainment's parent company, Vivendi Games merged with Activision.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2008 Electronic Arts nearly acquired Take-Two Interactive.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In 2009 Midway Games was acquired by Time-Warner and Eidos Interactive merged with Square Enix.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Consolidation of the video game industry has been high on the agenda, especially in the 2020s with acquisition of Bethesda (Zenimax Media) for $7.5bn in 2020 and Activision Blizzard for $69bn in 2023 by Microsoft (Xbox), along with Sony (PlayStation) acquiring Bungie for $3.6bn in 2022.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Development is overseen by internal and external producers.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The producer working for the developer is known as the *internal producer* and manages the development team, schedules, reports progress, hires and assigns staff, and so on.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The producer working for the publisher is known as the *external producer* and oversees developer progress and budget.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Producer's responsibilities include PR, contract negotiation, liaising between the staff and stakeholders, schedule and budget maintenance, quality assurance, beta test management, and localization.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] This role may also be referred to as *project manager*, *project lead*, or *director*.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A video game publisher is a company that publishes video games that they have either developed internally or have had developed by an external video game developer.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] As with book publishers or publishers of DVD movies, video game publishers are responsible for their product's manufacturing and marketing, including market research and all aspects of advertising.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] They usually finance the development, sometimes by paying a video game developer (the publisher calls this external development) and sometimes by paying an internal staff of developers called a studio.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Consequently, they also typically own the IP of the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Large video game publishers also distribute the games they publish, while some smaller publishers instead hire distribution companies (or larger video game publishers) to distribute the games they publish.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Other functions usually performed by the publisher include deciding on and paying for any license that the game may utilize; paying for localization; layout, printing, and possibly the writing of the user manual; and the creation of graphic design elements such as the box design.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Large publishers may also attempt to boost efficiency across all internal and external development teams by providing services such as sound design and code packages for commonly needed functionality.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Because the publisher usually finances development, it usually tries to manage development risk with a staff of producers or project managers to monitor the progress of the developer, critique ongoing development, and assist as necessary.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Most video games created by an external video game developer are paid for with periodic advances on royalties.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] These advances are paid when the developer reaches certain stages of development, called milestones.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] By definition independent video game developers often shortened to indie devs, create games without funding from a publisher and may choose to digitally distribute their games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Publishers have indeed provided much needed support for independent developers through various other means including making distribution platforms available.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Developers can range in size from small groups making casual games to housing hundreds of employees and producing several large titles.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Companies divide their subtasks of game development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Individual job titles may vary; however, roles are the same within the industry.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The development team consists of several members.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Some members of the team may handle more than one role; similarly, more than one task may be handled by the same member.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Team size can vary from 3 to 100 or more members, depending on the game's scope.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The most represented are artists, followed by programmers, then designers, and finally, audio specialists, with one to three producers in management.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Many teams also include a dedicated writer with expertise in video game writing.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Other positions, such as testers, may be employed only part-time.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Use of contractors for art, programming, and writing is standard within the industry.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Salaries for these positions vary depending on both the experience and the location of the employee.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A game designer is a person who designs gameplay, conceiving and designing the rules and structure of a game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Development teams usually have a lead designer who coordinates the work of other designers.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] They are the main visionaries of the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] One of the roles of a designer is being a writer, often employed part-time to conceive the game's narrative, dialogue, commentary, cutscene narrative, journals, video game packaging content, hint system, etc.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] In larger projects, there are often separate designers for various parts of the game, such as, game mechanics, user interface, characters, dialogue, graphics, etc.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A game artist is a visual artist who creates video game art.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The art production is usually overseen by an *art director* or *art lead*, making sure their vision is followed.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The art director manages the art team, scheduling and coordinating within the development team.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The artist's job may be 2D oriented or 3D oriented.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] *2D artists* may produce concept art, sprites, textures, environmental backdrops or terrain images, and user interface.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] *3D artists* may produce models or meshes, animation, 3D environment, and cinematics.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A game programmer is a software engineer who primarily develops video games or related software (such as game development tools).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The game's codebase development is handled by programmers.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] There are usually one to several lead programmers, who implement the game's starting codebase and overview future development and programmer allocation on individual modules.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] An entry-level programmer can make, on average, around $70,000 annually and an experienced programmer can make, on average, around $125,000 annually.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A level designer is a person who creates levels, challenges or missions for video games using a specific set of programs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] These programs may be commonly available commercial 3D or 2D design programs, or specially designed and tailored level editors made for a specific game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Level designers work with both incomplete and complete versions of the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Game programmers usually produce level editors and design tools for the designers to use.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] This eliminates the need for designers to access or modify game code.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Level editors may involve custom high-level scripting languages for interactive environments or AIs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] As opposed to the level editing tools sometimes available to the community, level designers often work with placeholders and prototypes aiming for consistency and clear layout before the required artwork is completed.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Sound engineers are technical professionals responsible for sound effects and sound positioning.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] They are sometimes involved in creating haptic feedback, as was the case with the Returnal game sound team at PlayStation Studios Creative Arts in London.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] They sometimes oversee voice acting and other sound asset creation.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Composers who create a game's musical score also comprise a game's sound team, though often this work is outsourced.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The quality assurance is carried out by game testers.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] A game tester analyzes video games to document software defects as part of a quality control.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Testing is a highly technical field requiring computing expertise and analytic competence.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] The testers ensure that the game falls within the proposed design: it both works and is entertaining.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] This involves testing of all features, compatibility, localization, etc.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Although necessary throughout the whole development process, testing is expensive and is often actively utilized only towards the completion of the project.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] During development, testing controller performance is essential.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p01] Using a gamepad tester helps developers detect input lag, button issues, and calibration problems, improving overall game quality.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game development is a software development process, as a video game is software with art, audio, and gameplay.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Formal software development methods are often overlooked.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Games with poor development methodology are likely to run over budget and time estimates, as well as contain a large number of bugs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Planning is important for individual and group projects alike.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Overall game development is not suited for typical software life cycle methods, such as the waterfall model.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] One method employed for game development is agile development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] It is based on iterative prototyping, a subset of software prototyping.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Agile development depends on feedback and refinement of the game's iterations with a gradually increasing feature set.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This method is effective because most projects do not start with a clear requirement outline.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A popular method of agile software development is Scrum.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Another successful method is Personal Software Process (PSP) requiring additional staff training to increase awareness of project planning.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This method is more expensive and requires commitment of team members.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] PSP can be extended to Team Software Process, where the whole team is self-directing.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game development usually involves an overlap of these methods.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] For example, asset creation may be done via waterfall model, because requirements and specification are clear, but gameplay design might be done using iterative prototyping.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] There are many types of commonly used programming languages for game development as more suitable.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Java and Javascript are top choices due to animation capability.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Python also has many libraries that can produce suitable game development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Minecraft for example is built entirely through Java.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] When programming the game the developers can either program the game animation using many graphical design libraries within the programming language.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Or if not they can load images direct into memory using the code to be the game animation.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Java has a high functionality for loading images into memory.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The late stage of pre-production may also be referred to as *proof of concept*, or *technical review* when more detailed game documents are produced.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Publishers have started to expect broader game proposals even featuring playable prototypes.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A *pitch*, *concept document*, proposal document, or *game proposal* is a short summary document intended to present the game's selling points and detail why the game would be profitable to develop.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Verbal pitches may be made to management within the developer company, and then presented to publishers.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A written document may need to be shown to publishers before funding is approved.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A game proposal may undergo one to several *green-light meetings* with publisher executives who determine if the game is to be developed.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The presentation of the project is often given by the game designers.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Demos may be created for the pitch; however may be unnecessary for established developers with good track records.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] If the developer acts as its own publisher, or both companies are subsidiaries of a single company, then only the upper management needs to give approval.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Before an approved design is completed, a skeleton crew of programmers and artists usually begins work.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Programmers may develop quick-and-dirty prototypes showcasing one or more features that stakeholders would like to see incorporated in the final product.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Artists may develop concept art and asset sketches as a springboard for developing real game assets.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Producers may work part-time on the game at this point, scaling up for full-time commitment as development progresses.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game producer's work during pre-production is related to planning the schedule, budget and estimating tasks with the team.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The producer aims to create a solid production plan so that no delays are experienced at the start of the production.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Before a full-scale production can begin, the development team produces the first version of a game design document incorporating all or most of the material from the initial pitch.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The design document describes the game's concept and major gameplay elements in detail.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] It may also include preliminary sketches of various aspects of the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The design document is sometimes accompanied by functional prototypes of some sections of the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The design document remains a living document throughout the development—often changed weekly or even daily.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Compiling a list of game's needs is called "requirement capture".
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Writing prototypes of gameplay ideas and features is an important activity that allows programmers and game designers to experiment with different algorithms and usability scenarios for a game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A great deal of prototyping may take place during pre-production before the design document is complete and may, in fact, help determine what features the design specifies.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Prototyping at this stage is often done manually, (paper prototyping), not digitally, as this is often easier and faster to test and make changes before wasting time and resources on what could be a canceled idea or project.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Prototyping may also take place during active development to test new ideas as the game emerges.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Prototypes are often meant only to act as a proof of concept or to test ideas, by adding, modifying or removing some of the features.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Most algorithms and features debuted in a prototype may be ported to the game once they have been completed.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Often prototypes need to be developed quickly with very little time for up-front design (around 20 to 25§ minutes of testing).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Therefore, usually very prolific programmers are called upon to quickly code these testbed tools.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] RAD tools may be used to aid in the quick development of these programs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In case the prototype is in a physical form, programmers and designers alike will make the game with paper, dice, and other easy-to-access tools in order to make the prototype faster.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A successful development model is iterative prototyping, where design is refined based on current progress.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Production is the main stage of development when assets and source code for the game are produced.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Mainstream production is usually defined as the period of time when the project is fully staffed.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Programmers write new source code, artists develop game assets, such as, sprites or 3D models.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Sound engineers develop sound effects and composers develop music for the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Level designers create levels, and writers write dialogue for cutscenes and NPCs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game designers continue to develop the game's design throughout production.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game design is an essential and collaborative process of designing the content and rules of a game, requiring artistic and technical competence as well as writing skills.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Creativity and an open mind are vital for the completion of a successful video game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] During development, the game designer implements and modifies the game design to reflect the current vision of the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Features and levels are often removed or added.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The art treatment may evolve and the backstory may change.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A new platform may be targeted as well as a new demographic.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] All these changes need to be documented and disseminated to the rest of the team.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Most changes occur as updates to the design document.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The programming of the game is handled by one or more game programmers.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] They develop prototypes to test ideas, many of which may never make it into the final game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The programmers incorporate new features demanded by the game design and fix any bugs introduced during the development process.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Even if an off-the-shelf game engine is used, a great deal of programming is required to customize almost every game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] From a time standpoint, the game's first level takes the longest to develop.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] As level designers and artists use the tools for level building, they request features and changes to the in-house tools that allow for quicker and higher-quality development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Newly introduced features may cause old levels to become obsolete, so the levels developed early on may be repeatedly developed and discarded.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Because of the dynamic environment of game development, the design of early levels may also change over time.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] It is not uncommon to spend upwards of twelve months on one level of a game developed over the course of three years.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Later levels can be developed much more quickly as the feature set is more complete and the game vision is clearer and more stable.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] During development, artists make art assets according to specifications given by the designers.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Early in production, concept artists make concept art to guide the artistic direction of the game, rough art is made for prototypes, and the designers work with artists to design the visual style and visual language of the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] As production goes on, more final art is made, and existing art is edited based on player feedback.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game audio may be separated into three categories—sound effects, music, and voice-over.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Sound effect production is the production of sounds by either tweaking a sample to a desired effect or replicating it with real objects.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Sound effects include UI sound design, which effectively conveys information both for visible UI elements and as an auditory display.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] It provides sonic feedback for in-game interfaces, as well as contributing to the overall game aesthetic.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Sound effects are important and impact the game's delivery.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Music may be synthesized or performed live.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] There are four main ways in which music is presented in a game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A game title with 20 hours of single-player gameplay may feature around 1 hour.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Quality assurance of a video game product plays a significant role throughout the development cycle of a game, though comes more significantly into play as the game nears completion.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Because game development is focused on the presentation and gameplay as seen by the player, there often is little rigor in maintaining and testing backend code in the early stages of development since such code may be readily disregarded if there are changes found in gameplay.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Some automated testing may be used to ensure the core game engine operates as expected, but most game testing comes via game tester, who enter the testing process once a playable prototype is available.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This may be one level or subset of the game software that can be used to any reasonable extent.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The use of testers may be lightweight at the early stages of development, but the testers' role becomes more predominant as the game nears completion, becoming a full-time role alongside development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Early testing is considered a key part of game design; the most common issue raised in several published post-mortems on game development was the failure to start the testing process early.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] As code matures and the gameplay features solidify, then development typically includes more rigorous test controls such as regression testing to make sure new updates to the code base do not change working parts of the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Games are complex software systems, and changes in one code area may unexpected cause a seemingly unrelated part of the game to fail.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Testers are tasked to repeatedly play through updated versions of games in these later stages to look for any issues or bugs not otherwise found from automated testing.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Because this can be a monotonous task of playing the same game over and over, this process can lead to games frequently being released with uncaught bugs or glitches.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] There are other factors simply inherent to video games that can make testing difficult.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Despite the dangers of overlooking regression testing, some game developers and publishers fail to test the full feature suite of the game and ship a game with bugs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This can result in customer dissatisfaction and failure to meet sales goals.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] When this does happen, most developers and publishers quickly release patches that fix the bugs and make the game fully playable again.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Certain publishing models are designed specifically to accommodate the fact that first releases of games may be bug-ridden but will be fixed post-release.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The early access model invites players to pay into a game before its planned release and helps to provide feedback and bug reports.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Mobile games and games with live services are also anticipated to be updated on a frequent basis, offset by pre-release testing with live feedback and bug reports.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Commercial game development projects may be required to meet milestones set by the publisher.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Milestones mark major events during game development and are used to track game's progress.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Such milestones may be, for example, *first playable*, *alpha*, or *beta* game versions.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Project milestones depend on the developer schedules.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Milestones are usually based on multiple short descriptions for functionality; examples may be "Player roaming around in-game environment" or "Physics working, collisions, vehicle" etc.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] These milestones are usually how the developer gets paid; sometimes as "an advance against royalty".
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] These milestones are listed, anywhere from three to twenty depending on the developer and publisher.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The milestone list is usually a collaborative agreement between the publisher and developer.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The developer usually advocates for making the milestone descriptions as simple as possible; depending on the specific publisher - the milestone agreements may get very detailed for a specific game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] When working with a good publisher, the "spirit of the law" is usually adhered to regarding milestone completion... in other words, if the milestone is 90% complete the milestone is usually paid with the understanding that it will be 100% complete by the next due milestone.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] It is a collaborative agreement between publisher and developer, and usually (but not always) the developer is constrained by heavy monthly development expenses that need to be met.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Also, sometimes milestones are "swapped", the developer or publisher may mutually agree to amend the agreement and rearrange milestone goals depending on changing requirements and development resources available.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Milestone agreements are usually included as part of the legal development contracts.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] After each "milestone" there is usually a payment arrangement.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Some very established developers may simply have a milestone agreement based on the amount of time the game is in development (monthly/quarterly) and not specific game functionality - this is not as common as detailed functionality "milestone lists".
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] There is no industry standard for defining milestones, and such varies depending on publisher, year, or project.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The *first playable* is the game version containing representative gameplay and assets, this is the first version with functional major gameplay elements.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] It is often based on the prototype created in pre-production.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Alpha and first playable are sometimes used to refer to a single milestone, however, large projects require first playable before feature complete alpha.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] First playable occurs 12 to 18 months before code release.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] It is sometimes referred to as the "Pre-Alpha" stage.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In most AAA game development, games are announced a year or more in advance and given a planned release date or approximate window so that they can promote and market the game, establish orders with retailers, and entice consumers to pre-order the game.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Delaying the release of a video game can have a negative financial impact on publishers and developers, and extensive delays may lead to project cancellation and employee layoffs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] To ensure a game makes a set release date, publishers and developers may require their employees to work overtime to complete the game, which is considered common in the industry.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This overtime is often referred to as "crunch time" or "crunch mode".
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In 2004 and afterwards, the culture of crunch time in the industry came under scrutiny, leading many publishers and developers to reduce the expectation on developers for overtime work and better schedule management, though crunch time still can occur.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] After the game goes gold and ships, some developers will give team members *comp time* (perhaps up to a week or two) to compensate for the overtime put in to complete the game, though this compensation is not standard.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Once a game ships, the maintenance phase for the video game begins.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Games developed for video game consoles have had almost no maintenance period in the past.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The shipped game would forever house as many bugs and features as when released.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This was common for consoles since all consoles had identical or nearly identical hardware; making incompatibility, the cause of many bugs, a non-issue.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In this case, maintenance would only occur in the case of a port, sequel, or enhanced remake that reuses a large portion of the engine and assets.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In recent times popularity of online console games has grown, and online capable video game consoles and online services such as Xbox Live for the Xbox have developed.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Developers can maintain their software through downloadable patches.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] These changes would not have been possible in the past without the widespread availability of the Internet.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game developers try to account for the majority of configurations and hardware.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] However, the number of possible configurations of hardware and software inevitably leads to the discovery of game-breaking circumstances that the programmers and testers did not account for.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Programmers wait for a period to get as many bug reports as possible.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Once the developer thinks they've obtained enough feedback, the programmers start working on a patch.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The patch may take weeks or months to develop, but it is intended to fix most accounted bugs and problems with the game that were overlooked in past code releases, or in rare cases, fix unintended problems caused by previous patches.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Occasionally a patch may include extra features or content or may even alter gameplay.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In the case of a massively multiplayer online game (MMOG), such as a MMORPG or MMORTS, the shipment of the game is the starting phase of maintenance.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The maintenance staff for such an online game can number in the dozens, sometimes including members of the original programming team, as the game world is continuously changed and iterated and new features are added.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Some developers implement a public test realm or player test realm (PTR) in order to test out significant upcoming changes prior to release.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] These specialized servers offer similar benefits as beta testing, where players get to preview new features while the developer gathers data about bugs and game balance.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Several development disciplines, such as audio, dialogue, or motion capture, occur for relatively short periods of time.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Efficient employment of these roles requires either a large development house with multiple simultaneous title productions or outsourcing from third-party vendors.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Employing personnel for these tasks full-time is expensive, so a majority of developers outsource a portion of the work.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Outsourcing plans are conceived during the pre-production stage; where the time and finances required for outsourced work are estimated.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Outsourced work is sometimes anonymous, i.e. not credited on the final product.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This might go against the wishes of the developer, or it is something they reluctantly consent to because it is the only work they can get.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] See Video game controversies § Lack of crediting for more information on this.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] However, anonymity can also be agreed upon, or even desired by the outsourced party.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A 2015 *Polygon* article stated that this practice is known as **ghost development**.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Ghost developers are hired by other developers to provide assistance, by publishers to develop a title they designed, or by companies outside the gaming industry.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] These businesses prefer to keep this hidden from the public to protect their brand equity, not wanting consumers or investors to know that they rely on external help.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Ghost development can involve (small) portions of a project, but there have been instances of entire games being outsourced without the studio being credited.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Ghost development has a particularly long history in the Japanese video game industry.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Probably the best-known example is Tose.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Founded in 1979, this 'behind-the-scenes' agent has either developed or helped develop over 2,000 games as of 2017, most of them anonymously.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This includes uncredited contributions to multiple *Resident Evil*, *Metal Gear*, and *Dragon Quest* titles.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Another example is Tokyo-based Hyde, which worked on *Final Fantasy*, *Persona*, and *Yakuza* games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Its president, Kenichi Yanagihara, stated that the approach stems from Japanese culture, in which many people prefer not to seek the limelight.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The game production has similar distribution methods to those of music and film industries.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The publisher's marketing team targets the game for a specific market and then advertises it.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The team advises the developer on target demographics and market trends, as well as suggests specific features.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The game is then advertised and the game's high concept is incorporated into the promotional material, ranging from magazine ads to TV spots.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Communication between developer and marketing is important.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The length and purpose of a game demo depends on the purpose of the demo and target audience.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A game's demo may range between a few seconds (such as clips or screenshots) to hours of gameplay.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The demo is usually intended for journalists, buyers, trade shows, general public, or internal employees (who, for example, may need to familiarize with the game to promote it).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Demos are produced with public relations, marketing and sales in mind, maximizing the presentation effectiveness.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] As a game nears completion, the publisher will want to showcase a demo of the title at trade shows.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Many games have a "Trade Show demo" scheduled.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The major annual trade shows are, for example, Electronic Entertainment Expo (E3) or Penny Arcade Expo (PAX).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] E3 is the largest show in North America.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] E3 is hosted primarily for marketing and business deals.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] New games and platforms are announced at E3 and it received broad press coverage.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Thousands of products are on display and press demonstration schedules are kept.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In the 2000s E3 became a more closed-door event and many advertisers have withdrawn, reducing E3's budget.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] PAX, created by authors of Penny Arcade blog and web-comic, is a mature and playful event with a player-centred philosophy.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] A game created in one language may also be published in other countries which speak a different language.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] For that region, the developers may want to translate the game to make it more accessible.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] For example, some games created for PlayStation Vita were initially published in Japanese language, like *Soul Sacrifice*.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Non-native speakers of the game's original language may have to wait for the translation of the game to their language.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] But most modern big-budget games take localization into account during the development process and the games are released in several different languages simultaneously.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Localization is the process of translating the language assets in a game into other languages.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] By localizing games, they increase their level of accessibility where games could help to expend the international markets effectively.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game localization is generally known as language translations yet a "full localization" of a game is a complex project.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] There are various essential elements in localizing a game including translating the language of the game to adjusting in-game assets for different cultures to reach more potential consumers in other geographies (or globalization for short).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The translation seems to fall into the scope of localization, which itself constitutes a substantially broader endeavour.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] These include the different levels of translation to the globalization of the game itself.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] However, certain developers seem to be divided on whether globalization falls under localization or not.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Moreover, to fit into the local markets, game production companies often change or redesign the graphic designs or the packaging of the game for marketing purposes.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] For example, the popular game *Assassin's Creed* has two different packaging designs for the European and US markets.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] By localizing the graphics and packaging designs, companies might arouse better connections and attention from the consumers from various regions.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The costs of developing a video game varies widely depending on several factors including team size, game genre and scope, and other factors such as intellectual property licensing costs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Most video game consoles also require development licensing costs which include game development kits for building and testing software.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Game budgets also typically include costs for marketing and promotion, which can be on the same order in cost as the development budget.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Prior to the 1990s, game development budgets, when reported, typically were on the average of US$1–5 million, with known outliers, such as the $20–25 million that Atari had paid to license the rights for *E.T. the Extra-Terrestrial* in addition to development costs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Koster reported average budgets were around $100 million by 2017, and could reach over $200 million by the early 2020s.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Koster asserts these trends are partially tied to the technological Moore's law that gave more computational power for developers to work into their games, but also related to expectations for content from players in newer games and the number of players games are expected to draw.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Shawn Layden, former CEO of Sony Interactive Entertainment, affirmed that the costs for each generation of PlayStation consoles nearly doubled, with PlayStation 4 games have average budgets of $100 million and anticipating that PlayStation 5 games could reach $200 million.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The rising costs of budgets of AAA games in the early 2000s led publishers to become risk-averse, staying to titles that were most likely to be high-selling games to recoup their costs.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] As a result of this risk aversion, the selection of AAA games in the mid-2000s became rather similar, and gave the opportunity for indie games that provided more experimental and unique gameplay concepts to expand around that time.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Costs of development for AAA games continued to rise over the next two decades; a report by the United Kingdom's Competition and Markets Authority regarding the proposed acquisition of Activision Blizzard by Microsoft in 2023.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Costs slowing increased from 1–4 million in 2000, to over $5 million in 2006, then to over $20 million by 2010, followed by $50 million to $150 million by 2018, and $200 million and up by 2023.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In some cases, several AAA games exceeded $1 billion to make, split between $500-$600M to develop and a similar amount for marketing.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In court documents from regulatory review of the Activision Blizzard merger, reviewed by *The Verge*, the costs of Sony's first party games like *Horizon Forbidden West* and *The Last of Us Part II* had exceeded $200 million.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Independent games or *indie games* are produced by individuals and small teams with no large-scale developer or publisher affiliations.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Indie developers generally rely on Internet distribution schemes.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Many hobbyist indie developers create mods of existing games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Indie developers are credited for creative game ideas (for example, *Darwinia*, *Weird Worlds*, *World of Goo*).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Current economic viability of indie development is questionable, however in recent years internet delivery platforms, such as, Xbox Live Arcade and Steam have improved indie game success.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In fact, some indie games have become very successful, such as *Braid*, *World of Goo*, and *Minecraft*.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In recent years many communities have emerged in support of indie games such as the popular indie game marketplace Itch.io, indie game YouTube channels and a large indie community on Steam.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] It is common for indie game developers to release games for free and generate revenue through other means such as microtransactions (in-game transactions), in-game advertisements and crowd-funding services like Patreon and Kickstarter.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The video game industry (formally referred to as interactive entertainment) is the economic sector involved with the development, marketing and sale of video games.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] The industry sports several unique approaches.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In the United States, in the early history of video game development, the prominent locale for game development was the corridor from San Francisco to Silicon Valley in California.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Most new developers in the US open near such "hot beds".
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] At present, many large publishers still operate there, such as: Activision Blizzard, Capcom Entertainment, Crystal Dynamics, Electronic Arts, Namco Bandai Games, Sega of America, and Sony Computer Entertainment America.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Many universities and design schools are offering classes specifically focused on game development.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Some have built strategic alliances with major game development companies.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] These alliances ensure that students have access to the latest technologies and are provided the opportunity to find jobs within the gaming industry once qualified.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Many innovative ideas are presented at conferences, such as Independent Games Festival (IGF) or Game Developers Conference (GDC).
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Indie game development may motivate students who produce a game for their final projects or thesis and may open their own game company.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Video game industry employment is fairly volatile, similar to other artistic industries including television, music, etc.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Scores of game development studios crop up, work on one game, and then quickly go under.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] This may be one reason why game developers tend to congregate geographically; if their current studio goes under, developers can flock to an adjacent one or start another from the ground up.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] In an industry where only the top 20% of products make a profit, it is easy to understand this fluctuation.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Numerous games may start development and are cancelled, or perhaps even completed but never published.
[src:game-dev/video-game-development-p02] Experienced game developers may work for years and yet never ship a title: such is the nature of the business.
